description:
A study developed by American Forests and Texas Trees Foundation showed that optimizing tree canopy, along with other surface cooling measures in greater Dallas would reduce heat-related deaths by 22 percent. 

The city of Dallas has identified several high-impact neighborhoods with low Tree Equity Scores and severe urban heat islands. Funding is needed to help Dallas continue planting shade-providing trees in vulnerable communities.

description:
This project is part of the Reforestation Campaign which has been promoted by the Jovel Valley Watershed Committee (CCVJ) and has been going on for 15 years. The campaign is launched every year at the beginning of the rainy season in May/June and concludes in September.  Our proposal is to design and revegetate the territory considering the various ecological niches to imitate the resilience of the ecosystems. We aim to restore ecological capacities such as biodiversity, water filtration and storage, carbon capture, and living soil.

We understand that reforestation involves more than just planting trees. That is why we not only give plants to those who request and have space for reforestation, but we also consider socio-cultural, ecological, economic, and spiritual aspects to make decisions together with the people and make proposals of local interest for the reforestation of the territory.

In the same way, the aim is to raise awareness and reconnect the urban population with their livelihoods and their territory. For this purpose, social reforestations are carried out, in which the general population is invited to reforest the rural environment.

description:
WHY MAMA? 

This is a call of the smallest generation (who can't plant themselves yet) to all adults to answer for their actions! 

It depends only on us what the house in which our children live will be like. 

This is the philosophy of #Mamaplantatree:
"Let�s help our children to remove the consequences of our actions behind us."

We plant new forests beetween fields, or FILTER WOODLINEs bettween field and twons to prevent dust storms; between lakes and towns to prevent wind storms; along roads to absorb CO2 and filter gas emissions to protect alongliving areas.

This year we can reforest more 340 ha of land, more than 3 million of new trees can be planted. 

Species planted vary from region to region and for every planting site is being confirmed with local ecologist, who authorize the plants type. 

These are our first locations, where woodline is needed as a protection from dust storms (more will follow).

description:
The �Green Schools� mission is born out of a need to scale the positive impacts of the Miyawaki Method through effective, equitable and efficient use of resources. The expertise and strength of each partner is utilized symbiotically to build maximum impact through collaboration, partnerships, knowledge and credit sharing, and putting proportionate skin in the game.

The mission will create dense native Miyawaki forests across 65 sites in schools and institutions in Aurangabad (rural) to build green-lungs for the schools and villages � Harit Maharashtra Abhiyan. The uniqueness of this program comes from the democratization of knowledge about the Miyawaki Method. We�ll train a team to oversee the implementation of these forests, as well as teams for each school to implement the Miyawaki Method effectively.

This program also focuses on spreading awareness about the need for native species conservation to schools. The program is designed in a way to instill ownership of the forests and the impact that the school will make through nurturing it to maturity.

description:
SAFE TREE is an innovative Eco-friendly Tree planting system which creates very favorable conditions at the newly planted plants root system, by maintaining constant moisture, stable temperature, dynamic ventilation and strong fertilization, thus it provides the plant the ability to survive itself securely and grow fast indeed.

Nigeria�s Ecosystem Restoration Project in Benue State, is a tree planting project that is intended to stop desertification, create favorable conditions for agroforestry crops and forest gardens and combat soil degradation and erosion.
Desertification advancing has implications on communities living in the Benue fringes of the Arid Zone in Nigeria. Forests are often cleared for farms, and cutting down trees provide a quick source of income for those living in poverty.
Our main target is to create agroforestry crops and forest gardens. To do this the first step is to plant and grow native trees for food and substances. After that when these trees are growing the farmers can develop agricultural cultivation near and below the trees. 
In the phase of planting, we add mycorrhizae. The mycorrhizae are symbiotic monoorganisms which are attached to the roots of the plant, take from them light to live and in return they dissolve inorganic elements of the soil, create beneficial components for the plant, aiding it in absorbing them and improving also the colloidal attributes of the soil.
In this way they combat soil degradation and erosion rejuvenating the earth.
The trees to be planted would be sourced from a Nursery site to be established in Benue State 
Our planting partners/community members would harvest seeds from native trees nurture them into seedlings at local nursery and subsequently plant them. We are proposing to plant 1500 trees in the interim with a prospect of scaling it up as the project gain more traction in the area. 
At this early stage of the project, the following native tree species would be planted. These native tree species work in harmony with farmers� bio-intensive gardens to help create a more nutrient rich soil. As the land within Makurdi zone regenerates, crop yield would increase, and farmers would be able to feed their families and sell extra products for income.
The following are the native tree plants that would be sourced from community nursery site(s):
?Mahogany (Khayasenegalensis) �400
?Mango trees - 300
?Locust bean (Parkiabiglobosa) -300
?Tenera oil palm (Eleasguinensis)- 200
?Ogbono (Irvingiagabonensis)-200
?Teak (Tectonagrandis)-100
Total :              1500

degradationCause: There is no degradation in this area, however we are planting trees to enhance natural resources for the tribal community and provide employment.
description:
This project includes the plantation of 85000 trees for Irula Tribes in Tamil Nadu, India. The Irular tribes, also known as Adivasis or Indigenous people, are some of the earliest settlers in the Indian subcontinent and have made contributions to its culture, history, heritage, and ecosystem. Unfortunately, they have become refugees in their own land and victims of dominant cultural hegemony, human rights violations and development displacement. The Irular tribes are semi-nomadic and settled as a landless and voiceless community in this region. Irulas are an aboriginal ethnic group and they mainly inhabit the parts of Nilgiri mountains and coastal plains in southern India. They are classified as a 'Scheduled tribe', and their population is estimated to being about 189,621 in Tamil Nadu.

Traditionally, the main occupation of the Irulars has been snake and rat-catching. They also work as labourers in the fields of landlords during the sowing and harvesting seasons or in the rice mills. However, after the implementation of the Wildlife (Protection) Act 1972, capturing snakes was prohibited in India. This has led the Irular families to permanently perform labour works, where they kept as bonded labour for long periods with inconsistent pay and low access to sufficient food.

Even though the irular's population is high in the identified project area, they are considered backward in terms of economic and educational advancement. The plantation project aims at engaging the irular communities in implementing on-ground activities which in turn will create job opportunities for the locals. An additional source of income will support their vulnerable economy while also bringing multi-faceted ecological advantages like enhanced carbon sequestration potential, improved greenery and wildlife habitats, increased food, fuel, fruits and flowers, and improved groundwater level.

description: Phoenix is a poster city grappling with the devastations of extreme heat, with summer temperatures expected to reach 114 degrees. The City of Phoenix wants to increase tree canopy in each of their 185 city parks to 25% and create cool corridors along areas heavily trafficked by pedestrians. Improved tree canopy in neighborhood parks will make it easier for people to safely leave their homes and improve recreational access particularly in low-equity neighborhoods, during the hottest months of the year.

description:
The Micha Ganu community restoration project is located in Chandananth Municipality ward no 7 Jumla Nepal. The community group established a restoration project with technical and financial support from Partnership for Sustainable Development (PSDN) Nepal aiming to restorative of the planet and its ecosystem by developing a greenery environment through plantation initiatives.Our restoration projects were started aiming to develop a greener environment by planting climate-resilient tree spices which are fit for the local environment. Projects initiatives support local people in coping with climate change distress. The restoration projects also support biodiversity conservations such as protection of water sources, controlling landslides, mitigating extreme floods, and contributing on maintain the ecosystem so that local people are improving their livelihoods using the benefit of restoration projects systematically and sustainable way. 
       Our project also contributes to mitigating global warming and reducing greenhouse gases in the atmosphere by developing a greener environment. Local people can be using the timber from the plant after 20 years based on the using policy of restoration projects and they need to replant tree 3 instead of the loss of 1 tree modality.

description:
Via the Trees Matter initiative Goumbook creates an opportunity to contribute to reforestation and restoration of ecosystems by planting coastal species such as mangroves and salt marsh would allow the coastline to recover, wildlife to return to the area, and ultimately aim for the site being turned into a natural reserve to foster environmental and educational activities.

Mangroves, which are rapidly disappearing globally due to coastal development, pollution, land-use conversion, and natural disasters, can grow even under harsh conditions like extreme salinity, high temperatures and anaerobic soil, making them perfectly adapted to the coastal intertropical zones of the UAE. Besides stabilizing coastlines, depolluting water and serving as biodiversity hotspots, mangroves also have an excellent carbon sequestration potential storing CO2 both in the biomass above and below the ground, which is why Goumbook is confident that offering mangroves as part of the Trees Matter program both locally will be a popular option for corporates looking to reforest and offset with an environmental as well as socio-economic impact.

description:
A Tiny Paradise: A Fruit Tree Garden and safe clean water for one village.

For a donation of 295� (here: please select exactly 1 "trees") you finance the installation of a Wells for Zo� - pump in a village and the planting of 10 indigenous or typical fruit trees surrounding the well.

A Tiny Paradise: Fruits and water for children without "lunch money" on their way to school.

A Tiny Paradise: Women often walk miles and miles for clean water and carry heavy buckets back to their homes, several times a day. Reducing these walkways while additionally increasing the water safety opens opportunities to start a business and thereby this donation is also a push for gender equality.

We provide safe clean water for about 700,000 Malawians in rural areas since 2005 and nearly 2000 pumps are already GPS-mapped (maps.wellsforzoe.org).
All pump donors can share a phrase which will be inscribed into a ceramic tile at the pump, e.g. Happy Birthday dear Papa. If you wish to do so, please forward your donation confirmation for this donation to info@wellsforzoe.org and send us a message which phrase you would like us to inscribe (4-6 words, space is limited on a tile).

After the installation (normally takes 14-21 days) and the planting of the trees you will receive an email with a link to your pump (see here for an example: https://wellsforzoe.org/pump-installation/2526/).

Please make sure to also send us a message even if you don't want to inscribe a message as we have otherwise no means of contacting you due to data-protection-regulations.

This is also great as a birthday-gift for people who already have more than they could possibly need...

description: Our reforestation project in the Los Tuxtlas Biosphere Reserve, Veracruz, Mexico, aims to restore the region's unique tropical forest ecosystem by planting 60,000 native trees over the next two years. Our focus is on revitalizing springs in pastureland parcels within the Cuetzalapan basin, which were once part of a thriving forest ecosystem.

degradationCause: Deforestation is the main degradation and its due to population pressure, bad agricultural practices,  poor land use practices, lack of adequate knowledge and awareness on environment, poverty, unsustainable utilization of timber resources, poor policies and policy implementation.
description:
Zambia is one of the countries in Africa with the highest rate of deforestation due to human activities such as charcoal burning, chitemene(cutting and burning of tree) system of farming and other activities. Northern Province and Kasama in particular, where our project is located is hard hit by human activities such as charcoal burning, bad agricultural practices and grazing for domestic animals. Chitemene system type of agriculture has caused extensive damage to the habitat because it does not only destroy the forests, but also the ecosystem. 

There is also a serious concern over the species of trees that are earmarked for extinction because there is apparently no program that is designed to restore the natural forests in the face of the continued damage that is done to the natural habitat. The natural setup has seriously been disturbed. 

Therefore, we as concerned and responsible organization in the region of rampant deforestation, wish to restore a target of 1000 hectors of lost forest by planting indigenous tree species. We aim to plant 2,000 trees per hector comprising of 500 hectors in Kasama district and 500 hectors in Lunte district in the northern province of Zambia in chief Nkole and Mukupakaoma. This project will be implemented in the lands that are independent from villagers. People near these areas depend on peasant farming and their source of income and some wild animal are left homeless.

description:
Fundaci�n Reforestemos is a non-profit organization that strives to be a leader in recognizing and recovering the environmental value of Chile�s ecosystems. We promote cultural change in relation to caring for the environment, recovering Chilean native forests and raising awareness about the importance of healthy, strong forests.

The initiative will contribute to the active restoration of areas degraded by bushfires in this national park that is highly visited from the citizens of Concepci�n. The Nongu�n National Park is home to a very important watershed, since it supplies water to more than half a million people, and its ecosystem services have historically been threatened by bushfires and illegal logging. The planting of these trees will be a great contribution to the protection and restoration of new green areas available to the community, which in Chile are under the minimum recommendations of the World Health Organization.

Fundaci�n Reforestemos is not tax deductible and can not issue donation receipts yet!

description:
This project was started aiming to make a green environment by planting various species of trees which are locally fit and suitable. This land is Nepal Sanskrit University Manpur Dang and local a group of people has taken 41 hectares of land in the lease for 20 years for purpose of making a green environment for fighting climate change and taking benefit from the fruit-based trees. There are many trees already available like around  2500  trees of mango, and 700 trees of Indian rosewood though around 400 plants trees of Indian bay leaf and teak were planted by a group of people last year.
This project's main objective is to make a green environment and to develop an Agrotourism or Agroforestry model in the coming future so a group of people has been working accordingly.  Another benefit of this project is to other adjoining communities people are also eager to the plantation in community and private land as a restoration model so they are asking for us to nominal support for the plantation program in new areas of the same location. 

  Our project also contributes to mitigating global warming and reducing greenhouse gases in the atmosphere by developing a greener environment. Local people can be using the timber from the plant after 20 years based on the using policy of restoration projects and they need to replant tree 3 instead of the loss of 1 tree modality as well as they can take benefit from fruit-based trees regularly.
The project will help the community to mitigate climate change effects and potential disasters as well such as soil degradation, heavy rainfall flood, drought, etc. Another major effect is other adjoining communities people can be practices such kinds of reforestation project activities because everyone has been highly affected by climate change and its related disasters. This project could be able to improve the living condition of local people by generating forest-based economic activities.

description:
The project is based in Nakuru and Bomet Counties that lie in the South Rift valley region in Kenya. These counties lie within the Mau Forests ecosystem that once covered large areas of both counties. The area lies within the tropical subtropical moist broad leafed forests biome and thus is marked by tropical montane forests. The two counties form important water catchment areas. Bomet County is the source of major rivers that flow to Lake Victoria while the project areas within Nakuru County are an important source of water for Lake Baringo and Lake Nakuru. The two counties have however experienced serious degradation over the years that affected local biodiversity, climatic conditions, hydrological functions, and even community livelihoods and economic activities. This degradation mainly occurred through deforestation as people cleared land for agricultural production and subsistence through unsustainable utilization of forest products. The increase in population and hence pressure on the natural resource base and land also led to negative effects including land fragmentation that aggravated degradation. The degradation and climate change through increased temperatures, reduced rainfalls, erratic rainfall patterns, increased evapotranspiration, and reduced infiltration rates, and increased population pressure and land degradation has impacted the availability and thus access to water resources. This includes effects on river streamflow�s and underground water levels.
Youth for change has been addressing this problem through repair of water infrastructure. This has mainly entailed the rehabilitation of boreholes previously sunk in the area through repair of the damaged hand pumps and other systems. However, the group realized that to address the water problem there is a need to address challenges facing the water sources through forest landscape restoration. This will entail rehabilitation of the watersheds through planting of trees in schools. The project thus target to plant 100,000 fruits and native tree seedlings in 100 schools (50 in Bomet and 50 in Nakuru) that also are target by the boreholes rehabilitation activities. The project will also support the establishment of tree nurseries in the target schools and establish and strengthen the schools environmental clubs. It also engage in awareness and capacity building on forest restoration especially through training, sensitization, and establishment of demo sites for practical learning. The projects will are designed and planned through community involvement, and the communities will also be actively involved in implementation and monitoring and evaluation of the project. It is expected that the project will contribute to improvement of the landscapes water catchment functions and water security, climate change mitigation and adaptation, improved food and nutritional security, improved awareness and knowledge and skills on forest restoration, create committed environmental stewards, and develop networks and communities of practice on forest landscape restoration, among other outcomes.

description:
Uganda is suffering from the rapid loss of its rainforests and is already feeling the negative effects of climate change. The reason for this is a rapidly growing population and its need for arable land and firewood.
 
The good news is that Uganda offers ideal conditions for reforestation. As part of our country program entitled "Lasting Solutions," we are taking advantage of this. We are working with many smallholder farmers and local organizations. In our so-called agroforestry approach, native tree species are planted on the same area as food crops such as beans and peanuts. Besides the future income from the wood, the smallholders can harvest them after a short time and sell them on markets. 

Through your support, seedlings can be raised in our nurseries every year, which are distributed free of charge to smallholders during the planting season. 

In so-called Farmer Field Schools, the experiences and knowledge of the smallholders are supplemented with expert forestry knowledge. In the courses, participants learn basic concepts and techniques of agroforestry and apply them practically through workshops in nature.
 
Together we can create sustainable solutions!

Tavy is used principally to grow staple crops like cassava and rice, but unfortunately the burning is often followed by an invasion of non-native species, which compete with trees.
description: Green Again Madagascar seeks to restore damaged rainforest reserves in Madagascar. True ecological restoration is more than simply planting trees, rather it involves a long-term commitment to assisting the recovery of an ecosystem. Ambodijirofo is one site where GreenAgain Madagascar has trained and employed several members of the community to plant native trees locally on privately owned land.  The original forest on this land was destroyed many years ago and the community is gaining collective interest in restoring it. The staff are now independently constructing a nursery of native trees and office for data analysis.

description:
Magombera Forest is a small but crucial location within the Eastern Arc Biodiversity Hotspot in Tanzania. It is a key habitat for elephant, endemic primates and used by the African wild dog. It is a refuge for threatened trees. Magombera Nature Reserve was officially designated in 2019 and Reforest Africa has been given the unique opportunity to co-manage the Nature Reserve. 

The project aims to both improve the in-situ conservation of the 2,615 ha reserve, and restore 120 ha of degraded forests within the reserve and wider landscape. We aim to plant 120,000 seedlings of at least 22 tree species including threatened tree species and other native and locally important species to restore the natural diversity of the rainforest. 

This will be achieved by supporting hands-on restoration activities in Magombera and neighbouring Udzungwa Botanic Garden, a recently established site for community-led restoration activities. The Botanic garden is being developed as a restoration training centre and source of threatened tree seedlings to drive forward conservation of threatened and native trees.

description:
GreenAgain Madagascar works alongside rural communities to conduct ecological experiments that are finding successful methods to restoring damaged rainforest reserves in eastern Madagascar. True ecological restoration is more than simply planting trees, rather it involves a long-term commitment to assisting the recovery of an ecosystem. 
Amarotandrazana is one village where GreenAgain Madagascar has trained and employed several members of the community to maintain a nursery of locally sourced native species and plant trees on privately owned land according to conditions of scientific experiments.  Degradation of the original forest on this land began many years ago and the community is gaining collective interest in its restoration. Skilled staff are learning the steps to independently operate the nursery and office for data analysis.

description:
TROFACO is a Denmark-based non-profit climate action enterprise planting trees in Cambodia and Uganda. The project was started by development consultants with decades of experience in community development and agroforestry. 

In Minziiro TROFACO works with a strong, visionary group of organised farmers called Kigazi Tukwatirewamu Forest Group. They own a huge area of rolling hills that used to be filled with trees, but are now barren due to deforestation. Last year alone they planted 30,000 trees!

The forest group decides which species of trees to plant, and they also decide where they are planted. As they have a say in the project, they are invested in it, and therefore take particular care of the trees. 

The project is based on a contract with the community, co-signed by local authorities and by our NGO partner. Our NGO partner visits the site frequently in order to talk to community and check the trees. TROFACO will visit at least once per year and take documentation pictures. These pictures will be uploaded to our website with GPS coordinates. 30% percent of the amount donated to this project will be set aside in a separate fund that will distribute the funds to the forest group over the next 20 years. 

So, we are proud to provide real benefits to the community and surviving trees for the climate and our globe.

description:
Ancient rainforest, waterfalls, crystal clear crater lakes, and home to Tree Kangaroos and Cassowaries. When you explore the Atherton Tablelands you notice that between lush rainforest patches lies long stretches of paddocks and grazing land. In the past 200 years there has been extensive clearing of the lowlands transforming the area from dense rainforest to savannah, fragmented remnants of rainforest, and expanses of agricultural land for animal production. 

Currently the amount of native vegetation remaining in the Atherton Tablelands is 41�49 per cent of its former size. The majority of this is broken up into small fragments, disconnected from one another and creating challenges for wildlife to pass between fragments.

A key aim of this project is to expand wildlife corridors for connectivity between forest fragments. Connectivity includes the implementation of wildlife corridors of trees that connect fragmented forest. Animals use these wildlife corridors as crossing bare paddocks or through urban areas is highly risky. Connectivity provides access to new and varied habitat and improves the genetic dispersal and variation in previously isolated populations.

description:
The project envisages implementing a biodiverse stratified agroforestry pilot project on community-owned lands affected by deforestation, with the active involvement of the inhabitants of Lernavan village. 
Particularly for the sloping treeless area, which is degrading due to intensive grazing, restoration is essential for preventing soil erosion, contributing to water infiltration and retention, regulating of local climate, and creating green spaces. It is planned to create a biodiverse stratified agroforestry system, including broadleaved forest trees as well as fruit trees and a variety of fruit- and nut-bearing shrubs and bushes in combination with grains/legumes or fodder plants. 
Due to the existence of micro-areas with different slope conditions within the designated site, there will be different planting concepts and patterns, which reach from alley cropping with rows of trees and shrubs bordering the terraces, where different agricultural crops will be grown to pure reforestation islands and belts in the steeper areas. 
Whilst on the terraced area, although the terraces are eroding, it will mostly be possible to prepare the ground mechanically. The steepness and complexity of the terrain above the terraced area and on the adjacent protrusion make it necessary that the preparation of the ground will be carried out mainly by hand. In this area, the surface flow of water during high intensity rainfalls also causes damage to the underlying lands. In the future, the plantings will play a water-regulating role and, at the same time, will have a recreational significance. 
Members of the village will take care of the plantings and manage both the trees and shrubs, as well as the agricultural crops. This includes weeding, soil preparation, and mulching, as well as pruning of the trees and shrubs. During the first years also partial irrigation during prolonged dry periods in the growing season may be required to support the establishment of the trees and shrubs. Whilst taking care that the plants receive only the water needed in order to support the development of a strong and well-developed root system, water will be provided as long as necessary.
Former experience with reforestation in the villages of Ttujur (Aragatsotn), Chambarak (Gegharkunik), and Dzoraglugh (Aragatsotn) shows that metallic grids must fence the planted areas in order to prevent the intrusion of cattle and sheep during the grazing period, as they can easily destroy newly planted saplings and severely damage and inhibit the growth of young trees. In addition, a guard has to be appointed, who takes the responsibility of checking the fencing for damage regularly and repairing possible damages in order to guarantee that animals cannot enter the site. Currently, there is no other secure option of fully excluding animals from the planting sites. After some years, when the trees are high and robust enough, the fences will be donated to the village, and they can use them for fencing other new-planted areas. This approach will further ensure the sustainability of the project.

description: The project is geared towards the regeneration and restoration of the waste land within the water tower of Mt. Elgon. This region serves the entire region of great L. Victoria that shares its waters into Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania and at the same time it is the source of River .Nile that runs into Red sea through Ethiopia and Egypt. We are focusing on giving the correct information, practices and training to the farmers in this region whom have been using traditionally methods for land preparation i.e. bush fallowing that has resulted into ecological disaster via erosion, bush fires and deforestation, On the other hand population explosion has resulted into great danger to the ecosystem since people have encroached the forest to get land for farming and also grazing field field. Landslides have been of great danger especially during long and heavy rains seasons. We encourage the farmers by giving them the best species that are indigenous but leguminous in nature such that they restore soil fertility while also using them for financial gain on managed harvesting program. This also help to prevent people going for timber in the forest and also other medical plant from the forest. Our team educate them on the self-sustainability of the program and also land preparation, nursery management, transplanting as well tree maintenance and management.

description:
Volunt2Thai is a village development project with a focus on underprivileged children. Because in Thailand, especially in the northeast of Thailand, people are very poor. Individual family members are often forced to leave their children and elderly for long periods of time to travel to urban centers or abroad for work. The situation is very bad for the development of the children who are left without their parents. The project is a regional development project in the poorest area of Thailand in Isan (Northeast of Thailand). Our main focus is to educate the children for a better future, instead of the exploitation, prostitution and crime that would otherwise await them without an education. Nature conservation is a very important concern for us, because the children of our area are completely unaware of conscious nature conservation. In the hardship of the families, at least 2 /3 of the forest in our area has also been destroyed in the last 10 years. The trees had to give way to rice and sugar cane, there was an extreme amount of illegal deforestation. 

Much wildlife has been lost and is threatened. What is left are very few refuges and food for rare wildlife and plants. Volunt2hai would like to counteract this and give the children additional lessons on nature conservation. It is about the reforestation of 1.5 hectares of forest on the ground, which is owned by our project. This forest should not only be a green lung and provide cool air while dry season but also provide food for animals and people. The tree price of 60 Euro is realistic, our area is already dry and steppe. Newly planted trees need intensive care, water and nutrients for the first 2 years, so planting requires a lot of labor. I really hope that we can get your support! You will help nature, the children, the volunteers who in the future will give instruction and awareness about nature conservation to the children. With kind regards Raimund Wagner for Volunt2Thai ---- 

PROJECT - ESTIMATED - COSTS - EFFORT ------ 

We start in the "desert" ..., no shade no water ... 

Brief introduction: We plant Fruit trees, for example, mango, very good rapid growth, (if enough water, tree height up to 30 meters high. Trees are planted with treated root ball. Cost per tree about 800 baht, approx.: 21.99 euros. But mango is pollinated by flies. Therefore it needs many other tree species (each also about the 20 euros, height already 200 cm +) so that also the bees can be settled (bees are almost extinct with us - no food / they are emphasis! "Necessary structure fauna" / flora. (Green island of life) Provision costs: Additional soil (dam) / 400 truckloads (each 17 Euro) 6000 Euro including tractor Manpower for tree setting (digging, soil preparation, possible additional costs, small excavator ) 3 men (10 days a/ 60 euros, including food + tools) Potting soil / ash and wood chips under the roots, when planting, about 500 euros E-water pump / distributor 400 euros (The well is already drilled 45 meters deep cost 2000 euros) Necessary tree fertilizer, about 200 euros / 100 trees 2x a year (pig manure does not work / termites, other insects) Agricultural net for tree protection about 100 euros (on tree bus device) minimizing dehydration / protection - no direct sun Water hose, UV and heat resistant 120 meters (high pressure) 400 Euro (is still cheaper than steel pipes) 1 man permanently employee/ farmer about 300 euros wage / month during dry season and planting (about 4 months) Trees must always be moist on the bark / time saving with high pressure sprinkler, High quality about 200 + Euros Unforeseen costs / logistics 1000 Euro incl. car / tools etc. / breakage / repairs / replacement

description:
Boongarri Creek, Euramo, is being revegetated with native flora species that will provide habitat for endangered fauna such as the Southern Cassowary and Ulysses Butterfly.

Contribute today to make more forests and a greener world.

Each tree planted also improves water quality that flows through this tributary to the Great Barrier Reef on the east coast of Australia. Be the change and make a positive difference today.

Help us rehabilitate this ecosystem and create more nature, one tree at a time.

description:
One of the most pressing issues in modern times is climate change, or the amount of carbon in the atmosphere contributing to global warming.

And through decades of chemical-industrial farming, our soil is completely deprived of carbon, which is one of the main ingredients of a healthy and sustainable soil.

Experts calculate that the soil can absorb more than 10 times as much carbon dioxide as oceans, forests and plants combined. If we treat it right. And this is our vision.

Our community organization is based in Surin (Isaan), one of the poorest regions of Thailand, where agriculture is the backbone of society. 

There are thousands of small family farms, incentivized by government subsidies,  chemical companies and banks to grow monoculture, mostly rice. 

Through modern organic agroforestry, or regenerative no-till farming, we offer locals an alternative to chemical-industrial farming.

Our modern fruit plantations, ones certified with organic- and fair-trade labels, will provide farmers with additional income. 

We do not, however, encourage or incentivize farmers to discontinue rice farming,  which of course provides an important service to society.  And we will never plant our trees on 100% of an individual's land, to ensure that rice production is not interrupted.

Our organization not only donate trees to farmers, but we also help with soil regeneration, and provide techniques and procedures to increase yield. 

As a agricultural cooperative, we act as the intermediary or wholesaler to ensure farmers receive a fair price for their products. 

We also envision to open a small market in our village, providing our partners with the opportunity to sell their fruits directly to customers within our region.

description:
TREE THE SOLUTION

Humanity's activities on the environment in his quest for development have resulted in severe and continuous degradation of the ecosystem, thus posing a threat to his present and future living. The present scenario necessitates an alternative programme of meeting the wood needs of the country, mainly through plantation forestry and afforestation programmes.

Currently, deforestation constitutes one of the global development challenges. Specifically, it is the world's most severe long-term environmental problem, and Nigeria is no exception. 
The high level of poverty and illiteracy in Africa is directly linked to the current status of environmental pollution and degradation in the continent. The poor and the illiterate are often more interested in issues related to their daily survival than ecological management; this lack of interest and awareness often leads to more reckless environmental behavior, breeds more ecological problems and leads to a vicious cycle of poverty. Nigeria has more than 2 million ha of idle fertile land, desertification is ravaging in the north, and flood and erosion problems in the south; these are signs of climate change.
What can we do to save our planet? Lift people out of poverty, and improve their economic growth
Aerobic recognizes the global importance of sustainable development; we must connect the lines between climate change, water scarcity, and food security. To achieve this, we initiated a programme called the idea is to provide 1 million tree seedlings which will be planted and fostered by the communities and schools, especially in an area with flood, erosion and desertification. In this context, seedlings of fruits, vegetables, ornamentals, and forage seedlings which are our company products, will be highly discounted or, in most cases, given out freely to encourage rural communities, especially women, to take into tree planting. "The more tree you plant, the less you pay for fruit and vegetable seedlings", "The more tree you plant, the more free farming equipment you get". The aims are to produce more foods while growing the economy and mitigating the effect of climate change. 

You provide the land, and we'll plant trees - For Free!

To qualify, your land must be 100 acres, free of rocks and fallow. We supply all the trees and plant them on your land, ensuring management in your care. The program aims to grow crop circle tracts of trees to collect carbon from the atmosphere and preserve native tree species that may be endangered or threatened. Tree types will be selected according to your location, soil composition and climate.

[{'geometry': {'coordinates': [[[4.880348551800077, 8.106455264542744, 0], [4.887249623520455, 8.079736578524505, 0], [4.907184350925538, 8.08501187356638, 0], [4.90976753682914, 8.114169928113022, 0], [4.883644403896, 8.115635051862, 0], [4.880348551800077, 8.106455264542744, 0]]], 'type': 'Polygon'}, 'type': 'Feature', 'properties': {'lastUpdated': {'date': '2021-05-10 06:51:54.000000', 'timezone': 'UTC', 'timezone_type': 3}, 'name': 'Tree, the Solution', 'description': 'Humanity, and the planet that we have the privilege to call home, is facing no shortage of problems. Climate change. Biodiversity loss. Food insecurity. Any one of these issues alone threatens life. Unfortunately, much like buses, they have come along all at once.
There is one thing that lies at the crossroads of all of our problems; Agriculture. At Aerobic we know the impact of climate change is causing, for us we must connect the lines between climate change, water scarcity, and food security. To achieve this, we initiated a programme called �Tree the Solution� The idea is to provide 500,000 tree/fruit seedlings which will be planted and fostered by the communities and schools especially area experiencing the brunt of the climate crisis like flood, erosion, water shortage, herder/farmer clashes and desertification. 
The goal will be achieved through the implementation of the following objectives:
(i) To sensitise the farming community about the linkages between food security and climate change.
(ii) To promote adoption of climate smart farming practices (regenerative agroforestry). 
(iii) To ensure availability of seedlings in commercial quantities for farmers.
(iv) Creation and maintenance of jobs, improvement in average income for families with low incomes especially women and young people.
(v) To take urgent action to combat climate change and its impacts, end poverty in all its forms, achieve gender equality and empower all women and girls, sustainably manage forests, combat desertification, halt and reverse land degradation, halt biodiversity loss.

Aerobic Farms Limited is not tax deductible and can not issue donation receipts!', 'id': 'site_QIUmilG37a0Mvqc', 'status': 'planting'}}]

description:
Tsarasoatra is the main office for the region and the site of GreenAgain�s EcoSchool. The EcoSchool is a unique program where crew members work and study. In the countryside of Madagascar, there are obstacles to education, and like most young people, many of the crew did not complete formal studies to earn a diploma. EcoSchool is providing an alternative for these young minds. They are learning how to plant trees, maintain the nursery, work with a team, collect data in the field, operate a GPS and measuring devices, fill data in an excel spreadsheet on a computer, and skills of construction.  
The projects they are conducting contribute to data intensive ecological experiments written by scientists who are researching reforestation techniques specific to Madagascar forests.
The EcoSchool offers dormitories to host crew members who live far away and can also host visitors to conduct trainings at the field station. Opening our doors to exchange ideas and share knowledge is important to better our practice

description:
Habiba Community is an innovative start-up established in 2007 in the town of Nuweiba, in the Sinai peninsula of Egypt. Habiba Community follows the model of inclusive business for a circular economy and has a tremendous impact on the social and environmental fields locally. 
For over a decade, we have encouraged the local population to be more responsible toward the environment, 

Thorugh this project, we will support the expansion of agroforestry locally by supporting local bedouin farmers in establishing new agroforestry systems and by expanding our own agroforestry operation at Habiba Regenerative Farm. 

By combining different indigenous trees, shrubs, bushes and crops, the project aims at improving the soil's nutrient cycle, building a microclimate that will attract humidity, as well as improving food security and livelihoods.

description:
The site was a forest before. It was cut down by the state. Now the local communities (ethnic minority Thai and Muong) replant, together with TROFACO. 
TROFACO is a Denmark-based non-profit climate action enterprise planting trees together with organized communities. TROFACO was started by development professionals with decades of experience in community development and agroforestry. In Son La Vietnam we work with the Vietnamese NGO Centre for Rural Economy and Development (CRED). The community group decides which species of trees to plant and crops to grow with the trees. As they make the decisions, they are invested in it, and therefore take particular care of the trees. The project is based on a contract with the community, co-signed by local authorities and by CRED. CRED staff visits the site frequently to talk with the community and check on the trees. TROFACO will visit at least once per year and take documentation pictures. These pictures will be uploaded to our database (trees.trofaco.org) with GPS coordinates and timestamps. 
To boost local development and commitment to the trees, 30% percent of the amount donated to this project (as for all TROFACO plantings) will be set aside in a legally separate fund. As we see the trees are doing well, the fund will distribute the funds to the forest group over the next 20 years. So, we are proud to provide real benefits to the community and surviving trees for the climate and our globe.

description:
Cameroon includes circa 10% of the Congo Basin rainforest and although the country appears heavily forested,there is a continuous loss of natural forests (about 30ha/hour). Deforestation is strongly associated with timber harvesting, slash-and-burn agriculture, charcoal production and natural disasters.

In a bid to safeguard her then over 45.6% surface area forest cover (>40% today), the government of Cameroon in 1994 enacted the Forestry Law. The goal of which was to ensure sustainable management of forest and other natural resources.  One of the major innovations in the 1994 law was the concept of community forest that granted local communities access, use, management and marketing rights over substantial portion of the non-Permanent Forest Estates. As of 2011, 301 community forests had been attributed in Cameroon, accounting for 4% (1 million hectare) of the country�s forests estates. The South West Region of Cameroon accounts for 19 community forests, including the Etinde Community Forest.
The Etinde Community Forest is located in Fako Division of the South West region of Cameroon and has a total surface area of over 1000ha. It is part of a chain of protected areas within the Mt, Cameroon biodiversity hotspot and is home to forest elephants, chimpanzees, monkeys, drills amongst other amazing wildlife species. 
Unfortunately, parts of the forest has been lost to logging, agriculture and lava flowing from Mts. Cameroon and Etinde (active volcanoes). The deforestation rate is estimated at over 0.51% annually. 
As we speak, over 2/3 of all water bodies in the area have dried up leaving over 5000 people in water scarcity.
The aim of this project therefore is to plant 10,000native tree species in the deforested parts of the forest. We anticipate that the planted trees will contribute in recharging ground water & improving water tables (indicative of the return to flow of streams and rivers over time), restore wildlife habitat (thus reducing human-wildlife conflicts) and restock non-timber forest products (spices, fruits, nuts, honey, medicine etc that serve as an important source of income to the local people). Tree planting would also enhance the carbon sequestration ability of the ecosystem.

description:
GreenAgain Madagascar is restoring damaged rainforest reserves in Madagascar. Our approach to restoration is specific to the ecology of this region. We are scientists conducting experiments to find the most successful methods of reforestation, working with communities every step of the way. Our team of staff are local farmers dedicated to long-term commitment in assisting the recovery of an ecosystem. 
Ambodihazomamy is the location of one site where GreenAgain Madagascar has trained and employed several members of the community to plant native trees locally on privately owned land.  The original forest on this land was lost mainly to agriculture and charcoal production. The community is gaining collective interest in restoring it. After gaining the skills and knowledge while training at our EcoSchool, staff are now independently constructing a nursery of native trees and office for data analysis.

description:
The Guanacas Reserve is home to key species such as the puma, oncilla and ocelot, more than 150 bird species, 130 species of orchids, as well as endangered species such as Magnolias, the Antioquia Brush-Finch and the Antioquia Chocolate Frog among many others.
We aim to restore the habitat and natural dynamics of our wildlife by planting native trees in strategic sites within the Guanacas Reserve to promote connectivity between patches of forests that were isolated by agricultural and livestock practices.
Our rangers are people from the community who lead the whole planting process, they collect the seeds of native trees in the forest patches and propagate them in nurseries, then they plant the seedlings and apply organic fertilizer. Two maintenances are carried out during the year in order to reduce competition with herbaceous plants and promote growth.
We seek to restore harmony in man's relationship with nature, so we promote planting days with people from the community and visitors from nearby urban areas in order to generate environmental awareness and education.
�Help us protect the forest and its inhabitants!

description: This project will plant 140 urban trees at seven different elementary schools in Brownsville, Texas. Keep Brownsville Beautiful has a large number of student volunteers from their local high schools that they will engage to help plant the trees in the schools. The culminating event is scheduled to celebrate Arbor Day, during which they will also distribute seedlings to the community that can be planted at home. This project is more than just about planting the trees - it is about educating the community, specifically youth, on the importance of trees.

degradationCause: Deforestation for animal agriculture.
description:
The Daintree lowland rainforest in far north Queensland of Australia is a global biodiversity hotspot and is oldest continually surviving rainforests on Earth. Estimated to have existed continuously for ~110 million years. The greater Daintree rainforest is home to plant diversity unparalleled in Australia. As you walk through the Daintree you will see ferns and flowers representing every stage of plant and flower evolution. 

Deforestation for rural residential development and cattle farming has severely fragmented this ancient ecosystem leaving gaps in the rainforest canopy and damaging essential habitat for endangered species. 

We are in partnership with Jabalbina Yalanji Aboriginal Corporation who represent the Indigenous people of the Daintree and surrounding areas. We partner with them to plant trees and to support the interests of the Indigenous people of this area. 

The site, in the middle of the Daintree was deforested for animal agriculture (cattle). The site is now no longer used for agriculture and is ready for reforestation. Reforesting this site will return it to rainforest. When the site is reforested and maintained the area can be included into National Parks for protection. 

Reforestation in the Daintree is geared towards closing up gaps in the canopy, expanding existing habitat, and providing additional food and habitat for the Endangered Southern Cassowary - the iconic large bird of the Daintree.

description: Agaramthen Lake Area Afforestation aims is to transform vast swathes of unused lake area adjacent to the lake bund with an impaired ecosystem into a forest rich in biodiversity, a place that provides habitat for a variety of birds, insects, small mammals arising from the plantation of native trees and offering several ecosystem services such as controlling soil erosion, develop a riparian vegetation, improve groundwater recharge, microclimate regulation, reduce atmospheric pollution, reduce greenhouse gases, and help fight climate change and above all induce rainfall. The forest plantation development followed by monitoring and regular watering will enable the transformation of this open barren land adjacent to the lake bund with few trees into a thick canopy-covered forest with a three-layered climax community.

description:
Since 2019, American Forests has worked closely with the state of Rhode Island, municipalities and local nonprofits to develop and deploy a suite of climate and health tools that optimize urban forests for climate and health outcomes. As part of this pilot project, American Forests developed the first Tree Equity Score Analyzer (TESA), a state-of-the-art interactive map-based tool that can be used to plan tree planting projects at the parcel level and quantifies the specific local benefits to planting trees in that area.  

In 2021 and 2022, American Forests� grassroots partner, Groundwork Rhode Island, will be the first to use TESA to decide where to plant 140 trees in high-need areas � many on residential properties - in the cities of Pawtucket and Central Falls. Both cities have some of the highest rates of impervious surfaces in the state and suffer disproportionately from heat islands. Groundwork Rhode Island has strategically focused their planting efforts in private properties in an effort to positively impact Tree Equity Scores and where survival rates are highest. Funding from Salesforce will allow Groundwork RI to work in partnership with the Pawtucket and Central Falls Health Equity Zone to expand their successful tree giveaway program �Trees4Us� to homeowners, tenants and businesses in high priority areas.

degradationCause: Severe infestation by invasive alien plants � over 25% of the area is invaded; over 50 species of invasive plants have been found. Also, arguably, eucalyptus plantations using too much water. Little maintenance of plantation areas.
description:
We work in a degraded remnant of eastern mistbelt forest, an endangered vegetation type, in KwaZulu-Natal � an area that falls into the Maputaland-Pondoland-Albany Biodiversity Hotspot. 
Ferncliffe is still home to large mammals and a rich variety of birds and invertebrates. It is severely infested with alien vegetation, including creepers, which are killing even large canopy trees. The project aims to steadily thin and remove alien vegetation, and plant indigenous trees (10 or more different species specific to the area) to aid restoration and increase biodiversity. Clear-cutting invasives is not undertaken as shade is vital as a temporary canopy for young trees. Constant follow-up is required to keep the invasives under control. We try to plant older saplings, and water and protect them from browsers until established. We are the �Slow Food� equivalent of restoration projects: very much on site, committed to change over time! This is very labour-intensive, but unemployment is over 34% in South Africa, and we want to create decent work opportunities that pay more than minimum wage. This, as well as the older trees planted to up the survival rate and all that alien clearing, makes our trees a little more expensive. We also enable natural regeneration and rewilding in cleared areas, and work with other local organisations to advocate for the long-term protection and conservation of the forest. We are developing a nursery, and in the interim support local, independent nurseries that grow the plants we require. In the future, we aim to grow medicinal plants used for traditional medicine to help reduce pressure on sensitive areas such as Ferncliffe.

degradationCause: The dry season has become much more intense in this desert region.
description:
This restauration project is critical to the communities and forests surrounding Santa Rita Coapan.  In the ejido of Coapan the people depend on their environment for much of their livelihood.  Their land is under stress from increased severity of the dry season and increases in population.  This project will restore many hectares of natural forests which will provide habitat for many animals, ensure that underground water reserves continue to be replenished and minimize soil erosion.  

The mesquite trees that we plant will also support the natural local ecosystem by providing nectar to local bees in support of honey production.  

Also, the ejido is continuing to attract ecotourism to the area and a vibrant healthy forest is important to that.  The desert surrounding this community is full of much unique flora and fauna such as cactus and as such it does attract ecotourism.  The community is keen to protect and restore this area to continue to attract visitors.

The trees will be planted by members of Donate a Tree to the World, volunteers and members of the ejido of Santa Maria Coapan.

The project involves and aids significantly the people of Santa Maria Coapan.  It includes an education program that will help give them tools and understanding so they can live more sustainably and successfully with their environment.  The people of this community will do most of the planting with our guidance.

description:
Green Again Madagascar is restoring the tropical rainforests of eastern Madagascar, which are habitats for lemurs and thousands of plant and wildlife species found nowhere else on Earth. Nearly 90% of Madagascar�s biodiverse rainforests have been lost to unsustainable agriculture. Green Again employs, trains, and partners with subsistence farmers to re-establish diverse native tree plantations by planting 78 species of trees endemic to eastern Madagascar. 

We know that tree-planting on its own won�t guarantee the survival of these rainforests. Long-term changes in the environment require youth involvement, as they will be the next generation of farmers, forest users, fishers, and community leaders. 

To enhance environmental awareness, Green Again Restoration is launching an EcoEducation program in collaboration with the local schools at the rural locations where we work to protect the forests. We aim to provide opportunities for children to plant trees, become aware of the condition of their surrounding forest, and grow enthusiastic about what they can do to help.

The Green Again planting process from seedling to the end of extended care lasts 3-5 years for every tree.  At the end of the process, trees are more likely to survive through to maturity.  From planting thousands of trees and collecting scientific data for over 8 years, we are ready to pass valuable knowledge to a younger generation and include them in the restoration process.

description: London Borough of Tower Hamlets is one of the most densely populated areas of London. At the time of the 2011 Census, 69% of the ward population were black & minority ethnic groups (BME). Bromley South has very few open spaces and parks, and the importance of improving Furze Green cannot be underestimated. Furze Green, which is already surrounded on all sides by multi-story residential properties, will also see the construction of a new primary school, two new housing developments, and the extension of a secondary school. This project looks to improve the visual amenity for Furze Green, create a healthier and happier climate, increase canopy cover and biodiversity as well as use of the park by residents. The project includes consultation of local residents on the planting of 250 whips in an urban micro-forest whilst engaging 5 local school groups in the planting of the trees. These trees will complement other planting that Trees for Cities has done, be well maintained and be a valuable resource for an increasingly densely populated area. Salesforce employees in the area will also be engaged in planting the trees.

description:
The 5MTrees initiative�s goal is to plant 5 million trees before the year 2030, this program also involves the removal of Alien Invasive vegetation. This program will help towards achieving South Africa�s AFR100 and Global Sustainable goals commitments.

The 5MTrees project is defined by its threefold nature of the following sequential objectives:
- The removal of alien invasive vegetation 
- The planting of indigenous vegetation to increase tree and bush cover 
- The care and maintenance of the planted vegetation in its vulnerable growth period.
This approach type has enabled LLB to zone in on Land Degradation Neutrality(LDN) and Forest Landscape Restoration (FLR) activities. The 5MTrees is more than just planting trees, as illustrated by the relationships of SDG 15 as central to achieving the other number of goals and sub goals of other SDG�s. Goal 15 promotes sustainable use of land, smart and resilient agriculture and efficient use of resources. Our project brings in to play other key interventions such as food security and
climate action, all in the pursuit of resilient communities in our vulnerable areas.

description:
Working with schools in Kitui County in Kenya, we engage students and teachers in learning about the environmental benefits of planting trees. The project also demonstrates best practice in tree planting, and supports parents to plant trees on their own land. The main species planted is an indigenous, fast growing and drought resistant tree called �Melia Volkensii�. This tree has many uses, including edible leaves used as fodder for animals, pruning branches for firewood, and as forage for bees. It can be easily integrated into crops through agroforestry farming systems. We are also planting indigenous species to provide shade, fruits and other products. 

The project aims to work with up to 20 schools to plant areas of their grounds with plantations of around 1 acre. Farming communities will also be engaged, planting trees on their land.

degradationCause: Clearing rainforest for agriculture - cow paddocks.
description:
Intensive clearing of subtropical northern NSW has left a fragmented forest immensely vulnerable to threats of climate change, bushfires, and invasive weed degradation. This region was once the largest area of subtropical lowland rainforest in eastern Australia and now the remnants total less than 1% of the former size, approximately only 1000 hectares made up of small fragments scattered across the region. 

Wildlife corridors are connections across the landscape that link up areas of habitat. They support natural processes that occur in a healthy environment, including the movement of species to find resources, such as food and water. Wildlife prefer to use forest to move across a landscape as crossing empty paddocks and roads can be life-threatening.

This project is assisting with the restoration of a wildlife corridor that connects habitat from the eastern Byron Bay nature reserves up into the western habitat areas of Nightcap National Park. Over 50,000 trees will be planted at this location to connect habitat and allow wildlife to move between fragmented forest.

degradationCause: The 500-hectare location of Camp farm of the future used to be a cattle farm. Surrounding farms are soy-producing monocultures. Soil degradation and encroachment on natural areas are rampant. The expansion of monoculture is exacerbating problems such as food insecurity and unemployment.
description:
This project will be implemented at Camp Farm of the Future, a member of the Ecosystem Restoration Camps movement. 
Through the establishment of agroforestry systems, this project will prove to local communities� members and local authorities that there are eco-friendly and economically viable alternatives to the monoculture plantation model. 
First, a pilot agroforestry system will be planted at camp Farm of the Future. About 2,000 trees will be planted on a plot of 1ha. This area will function as a demonstration site. 
After the establishment of this demonstration site, at least three local smallholder farmers will establish agroforestry systems on their land and become in turn examples for the broader community. 
This project has also an important educational goal: each tree planted will directly finance an agroforestry training program that will educate and empower at least 120 high school students per year and will ensure the long-term sustainability of the project. 
The �Rural and Natural� cooperative is the organization responsible for implementing the agroforestry project and the educational training. The cooperative was established in 2020 by Camp Farm of the Future in cooperation with the local community.
Camp Farm of the Future, has a holistic vision for the development of the region of Caseara based on 7 dimensions: agroforestry and regenerative farming; entrepreneurship; education; eco-tourism; rewilding and ecosystem restoration; renewable energies; spirituality.
This specific project will focus mainly on the following three dimensions:
- Agroforestry, with the creation of agroforestry systems,
- Education, in cooperation with the �Escola Foresta� (forest school) to train local youth in agroforestry techniques,
- Entrepreneurship, with the development of a cooperative mode that will improve local communities� livelihoods and enhance food security.

description:
Established in 1979 and formerly known as the Men of the Trees (WA) our mission is categorised under 4 pillars:

- ENVIRONMENT - To restore degraded land, support biodiversity, and encourage the growth of healthy tree canopies in both urban and rural settings. 
- COMMUNITY - Our mission is to bring people together to grow, plant, establish and maintain trees to achieve a healthy, and bio diverse environment. 
- CORPORATE - Individuals, communities, business and government are provided opportunities to financially support ecological restoration across WA to improve the health and sustainability of the land and grow biodiversity 
- SPIRIT - We are directed by a vision of a world in which all people recognise the value of trees and forests 

We are an organisation who are able to mobilise thousands of people across the state to focus on revegetation of WA's ancient lands, reducing the impact of climate change. Importantly we reconnect people (especially those in urban areas) with nature, and inspire a love and respect of the natural environment. 

In Western Australia the botanical diversity is incredibly high. Botanically it is in the top 10 most diverse places on the planet. But it is threatened by land clearing for agriculture, housing and recreation that can bring weed invasions, animal road deaths, habitat destruction, species extinction and climate change.

The cost per tree: �3.1 is comprised of the following:

Pre-Planting Activities
- Land acquisition/negotiation with landholder,
- Site preparation including weed & pest control, species selection, reticulation installation.
- Preparation of planting event which includes up to 160 volunteers

Planting Day
- Setting up at the planting site 
- Induction of volunteers for Occupational Safety & Health
- Training volunteers in planting procedures
- Catering
- Quality control of planting
- Packing up the tree planting activity

Post Planting Activities
- monitoring and maintaining the site for 3 years.

description:
Bolivia is the poorest country in South America. The smallholder farmers in the Andes suffer under conditions of erosion, poor soil quality and climate change. There are, however, good methods to improve conditions with agroforestry, tree planting and water reservoirs.

Para�so Verde, which includes Camp Chocaya along with a host of other farms, focuses on agroforestry: mixed planting of fruit trees, deciduous trees and vegetables with the aim of improving the income position of farmers. Other goals are also important, such as improving soil quality and water supply. The deciduous trees function here as green fertilizers to improve the soil quality. The fruit trees (mostly apple trees) produce fruits and thus increase farmers� income. Our approach can help farmers triple their income.

This project thus contributes in various ways to the quality of life and income of the farmers involved and to improved environmental conditions.

description:
The Cool Climate (Clima Legal) is a permanent project of Apremavi. Its objective is to plant native trees to neutralize CO2 emissions, mitigating the effects of climate change and contributing to the conservation of biodiversity in the Atlantic Forest biome. It has different membership modalities for both individuals and corporations.

As well as the organization�s relevance for environmental preservation and conservation, the native seedlings that were placed in the land through the various projects developed over time also grew, in a continuous process. Among the many numbers and indicators that can be cited to represent Apremavi�s work, the impact on landscapes stands out, representing the planning of rural properties, the protection of water resources and biodiversity, and even the diversification of the source of income in the family farming.

Check out some before and after provided by Cool Climate - By Apremavi in different cities, contexts, and scales over time.

description:
The forests of Andalusia, Spain, are deeply degraded. 
Sierra Lujar has been punished by coal mining, then by pine monoculture reforestations and finally by a series of fires that have considerably diminished its biodiversity.

The association Semillistas works on the ecological restoration of this forest by means of methodologies of imitation of nature. We use various seed technologies (priming, pelleting and mycorrhizae) to make it possible to sow seeds directly in the forest.

As we say: "Nature doesn't plant trees, it sows seeds".

These techniques are much more respectful and economical than planting trees. In southern Spain it is difficult to use tree planting techniques with species other than pine. And these are a management problem and cause very recurrent fires. 
We need to recover the Mediterranean ecosystems with all their diversity of species. 
Our Sierra Lujar project this year will plant 20 species of trees, shrubs, bushes and lianas, as well as various types of mycorrhizal spores.  

The project will establish 20,000 plants in the winter of 2020, for which we will sow around 200,000 seeds.

We want to restore this mountain range to its former splendor.
We want the richness of its diversity to encourage the return of the shepherds.
We want to fully restore the sierra, which means introducing 4000000 trees and shrubs.

One of the great tasks in Spain is to solve the error of pine monocultures in forest areas. This, in addition to causing fires, makes traditional forms of livestock farming impossible. Livestock and Mediterranean forests are closely linked, and there is an urgent need to recover this form of forest management in rural areas.

That is why the basis of our plantations is the holm oak. The fruit of this tree, the acorn, provides food for countless wildlife, as well as for herds of goats. It also creates the conditions for the development of other plant species and mycorrhizal fungi.

If you want to know more about our projects and our sowing methodology, you can find us at:

https://semillistas.es/

Thank you for your collaboration in greening the Mediterranean.

description:
After 3 years� pilot Hara planting in coasts of Bushehr province, we are encouraging efforts of rural communities in Southern Iran for planting mangroves and artificial forestation of Hara. We started cultivation of Hara and other tropical trees in Bushehr province since 2018. Until now we planted about 60000 Hara tree in three sites. Continuing this work and increasing area of artificial forests of Hara tree and other tropical trees in Southern Iran need two main jobs. 1- production of seedlings, site detection and cultivation, 2- cultural programs for introducing the importance of this job. 
For the first purpose we established a greenhouse which is able to produce more than 5000 seedlings per month. The cost of each tree from seed collection to transferring to the selected site is 4 US dollars including: seed collection from mangrove forest: 0.5 $; Seedling preparation: 2.5 $; seedling cultivation in site: 1 $. The success rate of tree growth after 1 year in all trees sites was 98% in average. Benefits of this project: 1- Hara planting does not need watering or tree protection after forestation. 2- There is no limitation of lands regarding to non-productive sites for other industries or local communities. 3- Increase of chance of fish production for local communities. 4- Very low chance of firing and very high tolerance of heat and bad environmental condition by Hara forest.
For the second purpose we established a documentary production team which is producing short documentaries about trees. Each three months a five minutes� film is the goal of this team. The first film named �Hara Planting for the Beauty Planet� finalized and is available from this link: https://filmfreeway.com/projects/2313314 Benefits of the second goal: 1- introducing the importance of tree planting for local communities. 2- encouraging people to join this movement. 3- documentation of planting methods for other tree planting groups .

description:
The Indonesian rainforests are amongst the most biodiverse in the world, they provide oxygen for us and regulate our global climate. Nevertheless, 1.3 million hectares of rainforest are destroyed every year in Borneo alone. This is one of the highest deforestation rates worldwide. Day after day, the livelihood of orangutans and other critically endangered species is dwindling to satisfy our growing hunger for tropical wood, palm oil or coal. Oftentimes, forest is slashed and burned, resulting in annual forest and peat fires that accelerate climate change and endanger the health of millions of people.

As part of the One-Tree-One-Life Campaign, BOS Schweiz is supporting the reforestation of burned rainforest areas in East-Kalimantan, Indonesia. The tree-planting (fruit and timber trees, all endemic and mostly endangered species) happens on BOS Foundation�s land (in and around BOS Foundation�s orangutan rescue and rehabilitation center in Samboja Lestari). All reforestation activities there are carried out by BOS Schweiz and other volunteers as well as the local employees of BOS Foundation.

Please help us with this effort by donating trees for CHF 7.65 each (seedling + 5 years of care). Join in and experience how your commitment takes root on the island of Borneo, Indonesia!

In the past 20 years, the orangutans have lost 55 percent of their natural habitat. Wild populations have therefore shrunk by more than 80 percent in the past 20 to 30 years. But it's not just biodiversity that is under threat. More than 900'000 hectares of forest and land burned across Indonesia in summer 2019 alone. 44 percent of these were valuable peat forests. They store millions of tons of carbon and - if they are put on fire - emit four to 40 times more CO2 than forest fires in other tropical areas. For this reason, the World Bank estimates that peat and forest fires in Indonesia emitted almost twice as much CO2 into the atmosphere in 2019 than the simultaneous fires in the Amazonas area!

Peat and forest fires are an annual phenomenon in Indonesia. The 1997 fires were particularly bad. At that time, 1.5 million hectares of peat forests in southern Borneo burned, producing 13 to 40 percent of the world's greenhouse gases in that year. 8000 Borneo orangutans died. In autumn 2015, very severe fires happened as well burning uninterruptly for months. In an area half the size of Switzerland, 127'000 fires blazed and smoldered. They released 16 million tons of CO2 per day - more than the entire US produced at the same time. Again thousands of orangutans died in the flames and BOS experienced a massive influx of orangutans into its rescue and rehabilitation centers.

In 2015, 300 hectares of rainforest around the BOS rescue and rehabilitation center in Samboja Lestari also fell victim to the flames. Today, BOS is reforesting this area together with volunteers and employees of BOS Foundation and as part of the One Tree One Life campaign. The size of the ex-burned area not yet planted is 218.72 hectares.

The seedlings are grown in an own tree nursery. A mix of fruit and timber trees are planted - all endemic and mostly endangered species. 

In fact, the entire 1800-hectare area of Samboja Lestari has be replanted, tree by tree, because at the current location of the rescue center almost 20 years ago there was only degraded grassland. The reforestation work was largely completed in 2010 and almost the entire destroyed area was covered with a functioning rainforest when in 2015 (and also in 2019) the fire returned.  

The Samboja Lestari forest is not home to a wild orangutan population. In Samboja Lestari, BOS uses the forest for its rehabilitation and pre-release activities: Over many years, traumatized, injured and orphaned orangutans are prepared for a release there. In addition, unreleasable orangutans (and over 70 rescued and unreleasable sun bears) find shelter in Samboja Lestari on natural or man-made islands or huge forest enclosures. 

So far, many of the original animal species have returned to the replanted rainforest. Today, Samboja Lestari is one of the last green islands in the region that needs to be preserved.  

Since December 2017, the aim of the One-Tree-One-Life campaign has been to raise money for seedlings/trees planted accross our reforestation projects in East-Kalimantan (Samboja Lestari) and two additional reforestation projects in Central-Kalimantan (both present on this platform as well). Each year, the One-Tree-One-Life campaign enters into a new round of fundraising and comes with another volunteer trip organized by BOS Schweiz. If you are interested, please contact us: info(at)bos-schweiz.ch or visit one-tree-one-life.org.

description: We are regenerating a key place in the Uruguai Foester Biological corridor in Misiones province in Argentina. Our Reserve San Sebastian de la Selva is located in the heart of this highly important conservation area that conserves part of one of the most endangered ecosystems in the world, the Atlantic Forest, of wich we have lost aprox the 93%. We have been declared as IBA (Important Bird Area) and AICOM ( Important Bat Conservation Area) wich shows the high biodiversity in the area.
