description:
Borneo Orangutan Survival (BOS) Schweiz � together with its global partners � supports BOS Foundation in Indonesia to restore destroyed rainforest as well as to protect remaining forest areas. The ultimate goal is to conserve the habitat of the last wild orangutan populations living in these most species-rich ecosystems of our plant. 

Throughout the last decades, 80% of Borneo�s rainforests have been destroyed by logging, agricultural cultivation (mostly palm oil plantations), peat and forest fires, mining, as well as urban settlements. Orangutans have lost more than 60 percent of their habitat within the last 20 to 30 years. Today, they belong to the most critically endangered species in the world.

The SOS Borneo Project is located in one of the most threatened areas on the island of Borneo: The Mawas conservation forest, which is about twice the size of London. 

Historical Background 

During the 1990s, Indonesia aimed to fight widespread hunger by establishing a self-sufficient rice production. For that purpose, about 1 million hectares of peat forest were designated for rice cultivation and destroyed. In Borneo alone, 4.000 km of drainage canals were created to allow for this agricultural production. The plan did not succeed and the rice project has since been abandoned. 

The Mawas rainforest in Central-Kalimantan was and is amongst the most heavily affected and degraded areas. Since 2003, BOS Foundation in Indonesia has been responsible for protecting and restoring the wildlife there. This is critical because the Mawas conservation forest is home to more than 2.500 wild orangutans - one of the largest known wild orangutan populations in the world. In 2013, Mawas has been declared an area of high conservation value. However, illegal logging, pouching as well as wild fires continue to threaten the precious wildlife and its habitat. The drainage canals facilitate these illegal activities: They are frequently used to enter the conservation area and transport the illegally cut wood and bush meat. 
  
Canal Blocking & Reforestation

Especially in 2015 and 2019, large areas have been destroyed by peat and forest fires. Because peat forests store up to 20 times more carbon than non-peat mineral soils, such fires as well as the drying-out of the peat swamps themselves have a devastating climate effect. Until today, huge areas in Mawas remain degraded.

In the long-term, BOS plans to restore and replant approximately 70.000 hectares with more than 1 million trees. The first milestone, however, shall be a 1.000 hectares large area called Rantau Upak (in southern Mawas). Between 2016 when BOS Schweiz started to financially support this initiative until the end of 2019, 162.323 seedlings have been produced in own tree-nurseries and 144.4 hectares of rainforest have been replanted. Beforehand, 38 drainage canals (with an overall length of more than 60 km) were blocked to re-wet the soil, re-establish its natural fire protection and cut the illegal activities. 
 
The collection of seeds, the creation of tree nurseries, the production and planting of seedlings as well as the blocking of drainage canals is implemented by the local communities themselves with support from the BOS Mawas team. Thus, village groups are responsible for replanting and restoring those large peat forest areas.

Peat Fire Patrols & Alternative Livelihoods

Despite restoration and reforestation activities, the SOS Borneo Project closely works with the local communities and with regional institutions to combat illegal activities as well as peat and forest fires in this area. Measures taken include enhanced law-enforcement, education and the creation of alternative, i.e. legal and sustainable, sources of income through a micro-credit system.

Forest and peat fires pose a major threat to the rainforest and are a recurring annual phenomenon in this region. Local communities and other concession holders use slash-and-burn techniques to prepare their land for the upcoming planting season. The fire gets out of control and in some cases is burning for months (above and underneath the surface). The SOS Borneo Project supports the organisation of volunteer fire patrols among the villages, equips them and supports the establishment of wells.

SOS Borneo is far more than an orangutan conservation project: It combines the conservation of biodiversity in general with forest conservation, climate protection and community development. Please support this holistic approach! We, the orangutans and people in the Mawas area urgently need your financial support!

description: This site is part of the urban river valley system and has been identified as a priority restoration site by TRCA with significant opportunities to increase natural cover, improve water quality and quantity, enhance wildlife corridors, and improve overall watershed health. TRCA will assist local schools and community members with these community-based plantings. In total, TRCA will deliver 5 separate tree planting events that plant 140 trees/event, including four events with local schools and a fifth event with Salesforce employees.

description:
Let�s plant trees together and spread solutions with agroforestry and permaculture leading to a positive climate impact!

In the same go we will support rural people to reach food safety, to become ecologically and economically sustainable, and to get literate in how to preserve their livelihood. 

Hence, you are definitely making a great decision to support this project!

We are at the right spot for reversing massive erosion that washes away valuable soil that is polluting the lakes at the same time. Therefore, we start from the top of the mountain with countermeasures. On 3007-meter-hight, the Arba Minch University (AMU) has got 24.6 hectares which have been deforested by the local villagers leading to depletion of humus through erosion. Now, as part of the solution a meadow orchard and an agroforest shall be planted on at least half of this area. In total 17,000 trees will help to stop the loss of humus, while absorbing a part of the overmuch CO2 out of the atmosphere (more precisely absorbing the carbon (C) and giving back the oxygen (O2)). In the orchard and agroforest, we will plant trees like apple, pear, plum and chestnut trees. Below those trees partial shade trees and lower plants like vegetables will be planted for symbiosis. With this agroforestry and permaculture concept, we also introduce Terra Preta with several benefits. It will give long lasting fertilization to the soil and will increase the growth of plants. The preserved and improved humus will capture additional CO2 and will store water, which raises the level of the ground water as well. This overall approach, will help the resilience of these trees, create biodiversity and diverse nutrition. Planting, maintaining and later sales of surplus fruits and vegetables will create long-term income for the villagers. The villagers will be trained to train others to become multipliers for this high impact approach with great leverage effect.

In the name of todays and future children, thank you very much for your support!

This project is TAX deductible in Germany.

---------------------------------
AMU EcoVillage Project develops a sustainable high-quality lifestyle for rural regions in Africa. 
It aims to build a small prototype village with modern buildings from natural materials with renewable energy, resources-oriented wastewater systems for fertilizer and soil substrate production, self-sustained and sustainable surplus farming capabilities, a preventive healthcare center, a project-based learning environment for local villagers and students, and of course to provide internet access.
Additionally, it shall act as incubator and accelerator for green inclusive business start-ups. A sustainable forestry is only the start.  
In short it supports 16 out of 17 Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) from the United Nations (UN). 
 
Contact: project@unavision.eu

description:
Panama's Azuero peninsula is a degraded agricultural landscape that is only 7% forested. Globally, less than 2% of dry forest remains. Extreme forest fragmentation endangers our endemic wildlife through habitat loss & reduces the productivity of local farmland. Climate change already affects Azuero's wildlife & communities through intensifying sporadic weather patterns & producing increasingly harsh dry seasons. Increasing tree cover will help local communities mitigate & adapt to these changes.
Your donation funds planting of native and fruit trees along streams on farms within Pro Eco Azuero's prioritized corridor area. Together with farmers, Pro Eco Azuero is connecting remnant patches of riparian habitat and ensuring long-term farm resiliency. Each planted parcel has 5+ years of monitoring/ chemical-free follow-up & a commitment to replacement planting within the 1st year.

This project restores habitat in 8 communities along an ecological corridor (80 km long; 393+ properties). Trees planted in 2021 will benefit 7+ farming families, their larger communities, and many riparian-dependent wildlife species such as the critically-endangered Azuero spider monkey. Your donation helps us support Panama's capacity to meet its national goal to restore 1 million hectares in 20 years.

description: Our project is located on the territory of Manevychi forestry. The territory is covered mainly with pure pine forests, birch groves groves, less often - spruce forests, black alder plantations, mixed forests of pine, quaking oak and hornbeam. Wild rosemary, blueberries, and cowberries grow. Common animal species: white partridge, river beaver, field mouse, water vole, common housekeeper, river otter, spotted deer, wild boar, nesting stork black stork, and the owl is also found. Hares, foxes, wild boar, and wolves are also common. wild boar, and wolves are common.

description: This beautiful 38 hectare property in San Luis, Puntarenas (985m) has a similar history as much of the Monteverde region; functioning as a coffee plantation until 1980, followed by cattle pasture which degraded the soil. The land has been managed organically since 2008, and is now set to become a biodynamic coffee farm, using agroforestry techniques to shelter shade-grown organic coffee under bountiful fruit trees and towering tropical timbers.

degradationCause: The land has been intensively used for agriculture for many centuries leaving the soils bare and compacted. Groundwater extraction is higher than groundwater recharge. Intensive pig farms are increasingly polluting.
description:
Camp Altiplano is restoring 5 ha of land in the high steppe of south-eastern Spain, in the Murcia region. 
Murcia is one of the lowest income regions in Spain with high levels of rural to urban migration caused by lack of employment opportunities. This is a semi-arid ecosystem that has been severely degraded by deforestation, industrial agriculture, water exploitation and climate change.
The aim of the project is to create an example of a mixed regenerative agroforestry system that will serve as an educational hub for local farmers, while also proving that this type of farming is economically viable. 
The agroforestry system will be established on the keylines, and it will include a variety of perennial and annual crops (almonds, walnuts, peaches, quince, loquat, etc.) mixed with aromatics (such as lavender, rosemary, thyme and calendula) planted between the lines. Forty young trees (poplars, willows, olives and oaks) will also be planted to build a windbreak. 
The crops produced in the agroforestry system will then be sold, ensuring the economic sustainability of the project. A permanent groundcover system will be implemented to avoid erosion and increase soil organic matter. No machinery will be used on the land after the implementation of the system. Homemade compost and compost teas will also be used to build a healthy soil. 
The team at Altiplano is designing the whole project holistically, connecting all the elements on the land, from the buildings to the agroforestry system, from water management to the creation of regenerative livelihoods.

description:
Prevent desensitization. The main milestone of this project is the biodegradable system that we have developed, which allows not only to avoid the use of many plastics but also to generate added value to local communities. 

For years one of the main challenges in reforestation projects was the tons of plastics used. We have developed, tested, and validated a system that avoids the use of plastics and generates a sustainable source of income for the nearby local communities with the manufacturing of the biodegradable pots.

degradationCause: The people of Northern Uganda has experienced close to 20 years of conflict. During this time people were living in camps for the internally displaced. Forests have been cut to provide firewood and to burn charcoal for sale.
description:
Our Girls Education program is focused on reimagining a system where less than 1% of girls move on to secondary school from primary.  We are centered on changing persistent attitudes towards girl�s education and the cultural and customary traditions that keep girls from attending and excelling in school. We work together with parents, caretakers, schools and government officials to create this change. The program provides academic mentorship, textbooks and supplies, life skills and sanitary pads to 2,500 girls across Northern Uganda. Girls education is considered one of the most cost-effective and cheapest ways to reduce emissions. The faster female education can be scaled up, the greater impact it will have on the environmental, workforce, health indicators and population growth. 

It is poverty that keeps girls from completing primary and continuing to secondary school. As we provide families with trees every year they keep their daughters in school they will have a sustainable income that can enable them to pay for school fees. Our program provides seedlings, trainings and technical support. By supporting this program you help girls access the fundamental right of education and help the planet at the same time!

degradationCause: The 2019-2020 bushfires.
description:
Intensive clearing of subtropical northern NSW has left a fragmented forest immensely vulnerable to threats of climate change, bushfires, and invasive weed degradation. This region was once the largest area of subtropical lowland rainforest in eastern Australia and now the remnants total less than 1% of the former size, approximately only 1000 hectares while still home to a rich array of species, some of which are incredibly rare in Australia.

In 2019-2020 the fragmented forest and drought allowed bushfires to burn into this subtropical region and badly affected the rainforest. Tree planting and regeneration work in this area will be focused on fire affected sites needing immediate attention for recovery, degraded forest with high invasive weed infestation, and bringing back rainforest to where it was previously cleared for agriculture. The main site we are working on is adjacent to the national park and so the rehabilitation of this site and removal of weeds is necessary to protect the national park from the weeds. This site was once beautiful rainforest and we will bring it back through this project.

description:
Ejido Verde is a Mexican regenerative reforestation organization. In March 2020, Fast Company recognized us as one of the world�s most innovative initiatives. We restore degraded lands of rural and indigenous communities with native pine trees. Ejido Verde has planted 4 million trees during the period 2013-2019 in 13 indigenous communities in the state of Michoac�n, in areas with warm-cold climate. The planted area is 1,100 trees per ha with native pine species. Around one million tons of carbon equivalent is captured (243 ton/ha). Last year alone on average we planted 4 trees per minute with survival rates exceeding 80%.
The main purpose of these plantations is to increase the quantity and quality of environmental services to benefit people who live in rural areas as well as the inhabitants of urban areas.
Another purpose of Ejido Verde is to improve the conditions of the habitats that shelter the great biodiversity of the state of Michoac�n: a total of 9 thousand 509 wild species that places this federative entity as the fifth state of Mexico, only preceded by Chiapas, Oaxaca, Veracruz, and Guerrero.
Our project is part of an environmental strategy to contain deforestation in Michoac�n, and particularly in the Meseta Pur�pecha. This pine tree reforestation initiative emerged as a proposal for ecological restoration agreed with local communities.
The Ejido Verde project is conscious that forming new forests, or restoring them, is not just planting trees. Reforestation management should consider an ecosystem approach that allows for holistic management of these new plantations, improving the productivity of the area, conserving biodiversity, restoring environmental services, and improving the resilience of local populations.

Agroforst ist die Kombination aus Landwirtschaft und Forstwirtschaft. Gleichzeitig k�nnen �kologische Lebensmittel (Getreide, Kartoffeln, Gem�se, Obst) produziert und die Umwelt mit ihrer Flora und Fauna sowie die nat�rlichen Ressourcen gesch�tzt werden. Bei dieser Landnutzungsmethode stehen Ackerkulturen zusammen mit B�umen und Str�uchern auf derselben Fl�che. Durch die Anwendung der Agroforstmethode wird der Atmosph�re viel CO2 entzogen, da die B�ume Kohlenstoff in ihren St�mmen, �sten und Wurzeln speichern. Zudem beg�nstigen B�ume mit ihren tiefen Wurzeln den Wasserkreislauf und sch�tzen die B�den vor Abschwemmung. Zudem reichern sie den Boden mit fruchtbaren N�hrstoffen an, welche wiederum den Anbaukulturen zugutekommen. 

Agroforstsysteme haben �ber ihre �kosystemdienstleistungen eine g�nstige Wirkung auf die Umwelt. Warum wendet man sie dann so selten an? Mit der gr�nen Revolution kamen Traktor, Kunstd�nger und Insektenvertilgungsmittel. In der Folge wurden die �cker gr��er und die Bodenfruchtbarkeit wurde k�nstlich erreicht. Die Pestizide vernichteten aber nicht nur Sch�dlinge, sondern auch N�tzlinge und Best�uber. Ein Gro�teil der Landwirtschaft erzeugt auf diese Art billige Lebensmittel. Die Folgekosten f�r den Verlust der Bodenfruchtbarkeit, f�r die Wasserverunreinigung, f�r die Zerst�rung der Biodiversit�t und unsere Gesundheit erscheinen nicht in der Bilanz. Insbesondere heute ist es angesichts der Gefahr neuartiger Pandemien wichtig, neue Wege der Lebensmittelproduktion zu erforschen und einzuschlagen.
Das Agroforst-Projekt im Hochtal von Cochabamba in Bolivien untersucht, welche Baumarten und Feldfr�chte sich gegenseitig unterst�tzen. Die B�ume auf dem Feld (Obstgeh�lze, Begleitb�ume mit Ammenfunktion und Edelholzb�ume) sind in Reihen gepflanzt, die soweit auseinander stehen, dass dazwischen mit tierischer Zugkraft oder maschinell Ackerkulturen angelegt werden k�nnen, wie Mais, Kartoffeln, K�rbis, Bohnen und Tomaten. Die Begleitb�ume sch�tzen das artenreiche Produktionssystem vor Hitze, Trockenheit, Starkregen und Sch�dlingen, lockern den Boden, erh�hen die Bodenfruchtbarkeit und verbessern seine Wasserspeicherf�higkeit. Die Obstgeh�lze stellen eine alternative Einkommensquelle f�r die b�uerliche Familie dar und die Edelholzb�ume sind eine Investition in die Zukunft. Das Gesamtkonzept und die Bodenverbesserung sollen auch unter Klimaver�nderungen f�r sichere Ernteertr�ge sorgen, wodurch die Migration b�uerlicher Familien unterbleibt. 
Das Pflanzen der B�ume ist aufw�ndig. Zuerst einmal m�ssen die B�ume zum �berleben in dem hiesigen H�henklima (2.600 M.�.N.N.) einen guten Wurzelbalg haben, denn nur dieser gew�hrleistet, dass sie in der langen Trockenzeit gen�gend Wasser aufnehmen k�nnen. Zudem wird aus demselben Grund jedes Pflanzloch mit Kompost angereichert. In den ersten Jahren wird eine Bew�sserung der Baumreihen unumg�nglich sein. Die Obstgeh�lze ben�tigen ihren Erziehungsschnitt, die Edelh�lzer m�ssen regelm��ig aufgeastet und die Ammenb�ume heruntergeschnitten werden. All das erkl�rt die relativ hohen Kosten von 6,50 � pro gepflanztem Baum.
Der Projektstandort befindet sich im Tal von Cochabamba, in der N�he des Tunari-Nationalparks, dessen H�nge im vergangenen Jahrhundert abgeholzt worden sind. Die dortigen kleinb�uerlichen Familien leben von der traditionellen Subsistenzlandwirtschaft auf kleinen Ackerfl�chen und etwas Vieh. Weidedruck an den H�ngen hat zu Bergrutschen und Bodenerosion gef�hrt, deshalb sind Armut und Mangelern�hrung verbreitet. Die Klimaver�nderungen mit Wetterextremen und langen Trockenzeiten versch�rfen das Problem der Bodenerosion und den Mangel von Beregnungswasser derart, dass mancherorts die landwirtschaftliche Nutzung unm�glich geworden ist. Diese prek�re Lage gef�hrdet auch die Umwelt und die nat�rlichen Ressourcen. Es ist dringend erforderlich nach einer L�sung dieser Problematik zu forschen. Die Kombination von Nutz- und Begleitpflanzen in ein und derselben Parzelle er�ffnet eine Alternative. Sie bietet auch eine Reihe von Umweltdienstleistungen, die in Zeiten des Klimawechsels sehr wichtig sind. 
In Mollesnejta wird seit mehr als 20 Jahren mit Agroforst experimentiert und die Ergebnisse �ber NGOs mit Kleinb�uerinnen und Kleinbauern in der Region umgesetzt. Es konnte gezeigt werden, dass die Anwendung von Agroforst die lokale Biodiversit�t sogar an �kologisch sehr geschw�chten Standorten wiederaufleben l�sst, die Bodenfruchtbarkeit sich signifikant verbessert und die Bodenwasserspeicherf�higkeit zunimmt. Durch die agroforstliche Anwendung k�nnen Bauernfamilien auf vorher sehr ausged�rrten Fl�chen viele Produkte ohne den Einsatz von Agrochemie ernten. 
F�r den Erhalt des �kosystems der andinen T�ler ist eine z�gige Ausweitung der agroforstlich produzierenden Fl�chen wichtig, damit die Zerst�rung der letzten Land- und Wasserressourcen gestoppt werden. Aufgrund der bisherigen Ergebnisse werden heimische Baumarten und von der lokalen Bev�lkerung erw�nschte Obstgeh�lze mit der traditionellen Fruchtfolge von Ackerkulturen kombiniert. Mollesnejta, mit langer Erfahrung und breitem Wissen im Bereich Agroforst, wird die Projektleitung vor Ort innehaben, so die Pflanzvorbereitung, das Auspflanzen und die Pflege der Agroforstparzellen. 

Agroforestry is one way to increase carbon stocks in the landscape while also providing local people with some immediate benefits from harvesting of crop plants. This increases the incentives for enriching the land with long-lived plants. Yet, in many situations, we still need to find out, which types of trees and agricultural crop plants can be best combined. Hence, the aim of this project is to identify which combination of trees and edible plants facilitate forest restoration while at the same time meliorating the soil in order to ensure its productivity in times of climate change to avoid migration of local farmers. 
The location of the project is on the property of the Mollesnejta research farm in a semiarid Valley of the Bolivian Andes, located nearby the Tunari National Park, which was completely deforested in the 1960s.  The farmers in the Park live on subsistence agriculture. They keep cattle and cultivate crops with traditional farming methods but the yields are low. Malnutrition and poverty are widespread. Reasons for the low yields are that deforestation and overgrazing in the past has caused extreme soil erosion and landslides. In addition, intensive agriculture and the increasing exposure to extreme weather events due to global warming make farming almost impossible in some locations. All these factors put this unique environment and all the people who depend on it in an extremely precarious situation, and there is an urgent need to find approaches to counteract this environmental crisis.
Agroforestry, the combination of trees and crops in the same area, is an effective solution to this problem because this type of land-use can provide many ecosystem services. Therefore, agroforestry is considered a promising tool for restoring landscapes in face of climate change. For more than 20 years, experiments with agroforestry have been carried out in Mollesnejta and the experiences have been passed on to NGOs and small farmers from the regions. Previous results from Mollesnejta show clearly substantial benefits for native biodiversity and that even on extremely degraded sites, the conditions of the soil have improved considerably when managing the land through agroforestry. As a result of this, agroforestry allows farmers to achieve sustainable production and hence higher income on formerly degraded sites. We will plant native trees and other edible crop species (Date Palms, Apples, Indian Figs) that are preferred by the local community. 
Planting the seedlings is complex. First of all, in order to survive in the local high altitude climate (2,600 m.a.s.l.), the trees must have a good root bellows, because only this ensures that they can absorb enough water during the long dry season. In addition, for the same reason, each planting hole is enriched with compost. In the first years, watering the rows of trees will be unavoidable. The fruit and timber trees will need regular pruning and the nurse trees will need to be cut down. All this explains the relatively high cost of 6.50 � per planted tree. Due to their established experience with agroforestry systems in the region, Mollesnejta will be responsible for the actual management of this project including all planting, site preparation and maintenance activities.

degradationCause: While ANP is a protected area, forest loss persists mainly due to fires, logging, construction, slash-and-burn agriculture, and domestic livestock grazing. Our management zone, in particular, is under severe cumulative threats from fire, in addition to forest extraction and livestock grazing (zebu).
description: According to the IUCN Red List of threatened species, as of 2020 one third of all lemur species, a type of primate found only in Madagascar, are critically endangered. The driving force behind lemur population declines is habitat loss and fragmentation. Planet Madagascar�s forest regeneration project focuses on increasing lemur habitat connectivity by cultivating and planting new trees between forest fragments to create corridors. We hire and train local community members to build and manage nurseries and plant seedlings. Our forest restoration project also serves to empower local women in the community by supporting community members in creating a women's cooperative called Tontolo Maitso. We purchase many of our seeds from this cooperative, and the women are engaged in nursery work. Community members benefit via a salary-based program, and we have trained 107 community members on forest restoration planting techniques thus far. In the long-term, we aim to fill 2,500 ha of deforested land, connecting forest fragments. To date, we have planted over 60,000 trees with an initial average survival rate of over 91%. However, because of the nature of planting tropical dry forest within hot/dry environments we expect survivorship in the medium and longer term to be much lower. Thus, it is imperative that we plant as many trees as possible. For our project, it costs approximately $2.50 USD to plant one tree. This price considers all costs for running our reforestation project, including employee salaries, organizational overhead, nursery and planting supplies, equipment maintenance, travel, and capacity building. Our restoration project has created the beginnings of a conservation economy, which empowers both women and men in the communities where we work.

description: We are an environmentally focused couple living off-grid in Dolphin Bay, located in Bocas del Toro, Panama.  We are currently reforesting our home Island in efforts to offset jungle clear cutting for livestock and lumber trade. description:
In partnership with the Florida State Forest Service, we planted containerized longleaf pine and south florida slash pine between 7/11/2022 and 7/15/2022 (Lake Wales is rather unique among longleaf sites for being suited to summer planting).  This restotation project will create a number of benefits:
- Climate: Longleaf pine and South Florida slash pine are hardy, long-lived species native to Florida. Both are adapted and highly resilient to fire, drought, insects, and wind, especially compared to the slash pine plantations that they are replacing.
- Wildlife: This planting project will benefit multiple native wildlife species by improving the structure, composition and function of the forest. This is in large part achieved by the ability of native pines to establish and sustain a healthy fire regime. Reestablishing longleaf and slash pine at this site will improve wildlife cover, nesting, and browse habitat, and enhance the stand�s ability to burn in a healthy way by providing more continuous fine fuels. Native wildlife on this tract include whitetailed deer, black bear, wild turkey, quail, Florida panther and other species. Several threatened, endangered, and keystone/foundation species present on the tract include gopher tortoise, Florida scrub jay, Florida panther, bald eagle and sand skink.
- Labor: Planting was completed by a contract crew of 12 planters for five ten-hour days.
- Water: The Lake Wales Ridge State Forest plays an integral role in protecting and improving water quality in the Kissimmee Basin, which encompasses more than two dozen lakes in the Kissimmee Chain of Lakes, including their tributary streams and associated marshes, and the Kissimmee River and floodplain.

description:
The project would target an area of 200 acres of farmlands as part of this project in Andhra Pradesh. Practices such as agroforestry and multilayer farming model are predominant forms of TOFs in agriculture ecosystems. Such interventions have high potential for enhancing the revenues of farmers from their subsistence agriculture lands in addition to carbon sequestration that increases the green cover outside the forest zones while enhancing the livelihoods of farmers. Agroforestry is viewed as one of the best tools for optimizing farm productivity, increasing smallholder incomes, and building resilience in rural communities while contributing toward increased forest and tree cover. These systems reduce the stress on natural forests for forest produce such as fruits, timber and other NTPFs. More tree cover on private lands also helps to rehabilitate and restore degraded land and allows these private lands to increase their contribution to ecosystem goods and services. For example, increased tree cover stores carbon, helps to stabilize soil, and regulates water flow, reducing the risks associated with flooding. Increased tree cover also expands habitat for pollinators needed for agricultural crops, as well as other biodiversity. Trees can help communities increase their resilience to climate change and other shocks, not just through protection from extreme events, but by diversifying economic opportunities (through provision of fruits, wood, and other tree products).

The project aims to increase tree cover outside forests by promoting multi-strata agroforestry models through community mobilization & participation for enhancing livelihoods of farmers following natural farming methods. 

To achieve the above aim the project will work on the following objectives:
Objective 1: To increase the green cover outside forest areas and improving soil biodiversity & carbon sequestration through agroforestry.
Objective 2: Enabling farmers make a transition from chemical farming to sustainable farming practices. 
Objective 3: Providing farmers with additional livelihood opportunities.

description:
Fruits Trees. What is there not to love? We do budding&grafting on our ECO-Farm Lusangazi since many years and have a lot of experience in this field. As we have the great opportunity to plant a real Fruit Forest with Mango, Citrus and indigenous edible and medicinal trees in the Area of the Mchinji Forest Reserve we will contribute to the standard of this poor area. We will teach locals also how to dry their own Mangos for the hunger-season.
Project will be updated regularly, so stay in touch. If you have questions about it: Kevin@wellsforzoe.org

description:
Since 2000, this programme has supported UK community groups to achieve their tree planting ambitions in their local areas. Focusing on small-scale, publicly-accessible projects, we help to give people access to nature and put communities at the heart of local landscape decision-making. Over the past 20 years, ITF has supported over 100 such tree planting projects across the UK, ranging from planting trees in primary schools, native woodland creation, citizen science projects, community orchards, to the creation a 'food forest' this year at Oxford City Farm. 
 
At ITF we believe that access to nature (trees in particular) is essential for mental well-being. During the COVID-19 crisis, we all learned just how important is access to green spaces, particularly trees, woodlands and forests. However, the UK currently has one of the lowest rates of woodland cover in Europe, just 13%. The subsequent loss of wildlife and natural areas has meant that many communities are without easy access to trees or areas of forest, and children are not learning the benefits and wonder of forests. 
 
We see tree planting as having multiple benefits: not only does it provide valuable habitat for many threatened species, but it also absorbs carbon, helps control downstream flooding, stabilises and enriches soils, all the while giving people the access to trees and nature that is good for the nation�s mental health.

degradationCause: Soil erosion caused by unsustainable agricultural and grazing practices. The soil conditions are extremely poor and the water is absent. The project also focused on bringing water and moisture back by restoring three small lakes and improving the water retention capacity of the soil.
description:
Camp Rocciaviva sits on 73 hectares of hilly land and is nestled in a valley located close to the rustic town of Salandra (Italy).
While the northern slopes of the hills are covered by the remaining of the ancient oak forests that gave the name to this region (Lucania = from the Latin word 'lucus', 'sacred wood'), the Southern slopes have been severely over-exploited over the centuries due to intensive agriculture and animal grazing. The agricultural exploitation degraded the soil and turned this area into barren land. The soil is left uncovered and exposed to the elements and, year after year, the summer heat and the sun are further deteriorating it. These once forest-covered and biodiverse lands are now turning into a desert where the land doesn't have the capacity to capture and store any water. 

At Camp Rocciaviva, our group of motivated volunteers is working to prepare the land with the appropriate earthworks that will create a home for the little saplings. This will initiate perpetual land transformation with the aim of bringing the lush forest cover and biodiversity.

In addition to bringing back vegetation cover, we also aim at restoring three nearby lakes to further improve plant, insect, and animal biodiversity.

Join us and help us restore this barren region to the lush, green, biodiverse 'land of sacred woods' that it used to be centuries ago!
You can also join us as a volunteer - come plant with us! (more details here: https://ecosystemrestorationcamps.org/camp-rocciaviva-italy-2/ ).

description:
We will rehabilitate ex-forest-fire areas in Bawan village in Borneo. We want to support people in this village, of who about 80% work in gold mining, 15% in forest logging. We want to establish nature-based restoration as alternatives for earning money. 
Our organization is unique because we are 100% led by locals. We have worked in international organizations before. We believe we will have the highest project success because we're working from within the beneficiary communities and are socially well connected. 
We will plant local agricultural crops, forest fruits, and trees, to create biodiversity-rich systems that benefit local people, animals, and the natural ecosystem. We will focus on known vegetables for local markets, native nuts, cooking spices, and others.  
This activity will improve the income of farmers in a sustainable manner. We will reduce the area of degraded land, store Carbon, produce more Oxygen and water, and improve soil quality. In this project, we collaborate with indigenous communities, students in environmental sciences, and technical personnel from the Pandu Alam Lestari foundation.

description:
STRENGTHENING WOMEN TO PLANT FRUIT TREES FOR SUSTAINABLE LIVELIHOOD
The livelihoods of NYAKABINGO and KABUGHABUGHA communities are deeply dependent on farming and other land use, which provide incomes and food. According to our needs assessment 65% of these community residents are mostly small land holdings of between1-5 acres or less. Fruits for sustainable Livelihoods will work for vulnerable families who are most at risk from poverty and malnutrition.
Planting fruit trees is a popular way that local farmers can improve the productivity of their land. Through this project, we plan to establish two tree nurseries and train participants to graft and handle their own high-quality fruit trees. These can then be sold for a profit or planted to enhance their own farms. The project will focus on various fruit crops like mango, avocado, jackfruit, citrus, orange and paw paw which have high nutritional value and sell for a good price in local markets.
By helping farmers plant fruit trees on their land, we are helping farmers get alternative sources of income mostly marketing fruits thus reducing their reliance on natural forests, protecting them from overexploitation combined with the advantages of agroforestry; this is a positive step for both people and ecosystems living around Mt Rwenzori Forest National Park.
WHY BUILD A NURSERY BED
A nursery bed in the community will assume stewardship or ownership to the community we are serving. This will attract more community members to get involved in the tree-planting project because they will assume a sense of belonging to the project.
Producing seedlings is in the long-run cheaper and so cost effective than buying seedlings from other nursery beds � the main challenge so far. By training community members skills and knowledge will be gained e.g. to build an own nursery bed. The community will be much involved in all stages of the project and create employment opportunities like the full time nursery bed attendant and this will stimulate a sense of belonging to inspire most community members to join
In future it is planned to re -green and restore the degraded landscapes of NYAKABINGO AND KABUGHABUGHA rural communities that are severely affected by Climate Change. In this project, we will plant 500,000 fruit trees until 2030 that is when availed with necessary resources to establish a large tree nursery. Currently we start with a nursery bed costing USD $4564 for which we request climate change champions to help us mobilize and channel to this project in Uganda, East Africa.

degradationCause: This area has been hit by more severe droughts than normal during the dry season and has seen an increase in the bark beetle which damages many of the pines in the area.
description:
This restauration project is critical to the communities and forests surrounding Santa Rita Tlahuapan.  In the ejido of Tlahuapan the people depend on their environment for much of their livelihood.  Their land is under stress from climate change, increases in population and increased number of bark beetles.  This project will restore many hectares of natural forests which will provide habitat for many animals, ensure that underground water reserves continue to be replenished, minimize soil erosion and control harmful insects.  
This area is also home to several precious lightning bug sanctuaries.  A significant decrease in their population has been observed and the trees we plant will provide restauration of the forests where they live.  It is critical to the ejido that their habitats are maintained as they are an important source of tourism.
   
The project involves and aids significantly the people of Santa Rita Tlahuapan.  It includes an education program that will help give them tools and understanding so they can live more sustainably and successfully with their environment.
The high-altitude region of Santa Rita Tlahuapan is situated in the mountains between Mexico City and the city of Puebla near the active volcano Popocatepetl.  It is a beautiful, natural area that is home to many animals.  We are dedicated to conserving all of the fauna and flora of this beautiful region.

degradationCause: The degradation of the soil and the environment in this entity is due to the practice of inadequate cultivation techniques leading not only to infertility of the soil but also to its degradation in certain places of cultivable areas due to the population explosion.
description:
It has been for several years that we observe the excessive and abusive use of available land spaces by the practice of inadequate cultivation techniques leading not only to infertility of the soil but also to its degradation in certain places of cultivable spaces due to the demographic explosion justified by a high and unplanned birth rate, but also by the immigration of populations to the large centers exploring insecurity and which unfortunately ignore the practices of modern agro-forestry systems. This situation pushes the local communities of the territory of Nyiragongo to move to the Park in search of arable land in order to meet some of their basic needs.
To achieve this, the WWID / HFL organization seeks to enhance forest environments by initiating permaculture activities and protect the biodiversity of Virunga National Park.
Thus, nurseries of pre-selected agro-forestry species will be set up and popularized to the population with a view to recharging degrading areas and maintaining them on farms, which means that we will have to set up 7 nurseries of agro-forestry species but if we started from the price of seedlings we would be opposed to buying a seedling at the price of 0.8 $
In this perspective, this project is not only part of the Priority Plan of the Provincial Government of North Kivu, but also of the national sub-program for the management of protected areas.

description:
The Caribbean Tree Planting Project (CTPP) aims to plant one (1) million trees across at least ten (10) countries/territories in the Caribbean between January 2020 and June 2021. Through international, regional and national collaboration, the CTPP will not only ensure that trees are planted, but will also encourage public engagement in other activities centered around climate action. Components of the project will include encouraging farmers to engage in climate-smart agriculture and commissioning campaigns targeted towards the general public and behavioural change into making more climate-conscious decisions. 
The project is a youth-led initiative to mobilize partnerships across the private, public, and philanthropic sectors in order to achieve the UN's Sustainable Development Goals. More specifically, activities will address SDGs 13 - Climate Action & 15 - Life on Land. The three (3) core objectives of the project are:
1.To plant at least one (1) million trees and engage the general public in related climate actions across at least 10 Caribbean countries;
2.Promote Caribbean Youth and Caribbean Diaspora activism around climate change;
3.Highlight the significance of multi-stakeholder partnerships and collaborative actions, especially among philanthropists, required to accelerate achievement of SDGs.
The CTPP is coordinated by the Caribbean Philanthropic Alliance in collaboration with several individuals and organizations including the Clinton Global Initiative (CGI), the Trees That Feed Foundation (TTF), Jamaica Diaspora Taskforce Action Network (JDTAN), Jamaica Institute of Environmental Professionals (JIEP), International Telecommunication Union (ITU), Caribbean Girls Hack, Media Institute of the Caribbean, CARICOM Youth Ambassadors, Sandals Foundation, Grace Kennedy Foundation and LASCO Chin Foundation. 
With the latest collaboration of the Smallholder Farmers Alliance, together with Timberland and other sponsors, and their commitment to plant 25 million trees in Haiti over five (5) years, it is expected that the CTPP will exceed its projected one (1) million target by 2021.

description:
The Planet cooler restorers projects aims to restore the landscape in Njoro Sub County through planting of 5 million trees by the year 2030. The project will mainly plant fruit trees, Grevillea Robusta trees, and indigenous tree species. This will enhance the tree cover in the target area by 30%. The trees will be planted through an agro forestry approach in private farms within the location. To enable this, the planet coolers restorers� project will produce tree seedlings at its nursery site at Gachuhi center. These seedlings will then be issued to farmers to plant on their farms. Proper preparation of the planting areas will have to be done before the seedlings are issued to ensure that issued seedlings are actually planted properly. Farmers will be assisted with the site preparation work. Also, the farmers will be sensitized and capacity built to improve their knowledge and skills on agro forestry and restoration in general. 
The project area was chosen because of the wanton degradation that has occurred over the years. This degradation has had negative effects on the community�s livelihoods making them very vulnerable, especially to the impacts of climate change. This has mainly manifested through soil degradation leading to sharp drops in agricultural production and which had multiplier negative effects on the area socioeconomic wellbeing. The degradation also had many negative ecological impacts including reduction in stream flows of rivers such as River Nderit, River Naishi, and River Njoro. These rivers were important sources of water to the community. The rivers also feed the Nakuru National park, which has an alkaline lake. They are thus the source of drinking water to the wildlife in the national park. The area is thus also the catchment area for Lake Nakuru which is a very important biodiversity hotspot that is particularly highly famous for the large populations of flamingos that it supports. 
The project thus aims to restore the local forest landscape through agro forestry for improvement of biodiversity, ecosystem services and building of community resilience to climate change. This will be achieved through agro forestry tree planting, sensitization and capacity building, and livelihoods improvement through restoration work. Besides, the project will improve support community based natural resources management strategies, improve food security, engage in advocacy for landscape restoration, improve environmental governance, create job and business opportunities through agroforestry, improve water quality and availability for human and wildlife use among other benefits.

degradationCause: The native forest is disappearing to plant eucalyptus, mainly for cellulose production. They are much more likely to catch fire than native trees. Wildfires are becoming more frequent. We are working to regenerate land lost to wildfires and also plant native tree species.
description: Wildfires are a major threat to ecosystems. Wildfires are increasing their number every year and their catastrophic consequences. We are working to restore degraded land due to wildfires and also plant trees to prevent future wildfires in certain areas. In this part of Spain, the substitution of the native forest for eucalyptus has increased drastically the number of wildfires.  While eucalyptus is a very flammable tree that catches fire very easily and produces a lot of bark debris that propagates the fire with the wind the native forest composed mainly of oaks and chesnuts is much harder to catch fire and acts as fire cutters when a fire starts in a eucalyptus area. Therefore we are also planting these trees around eucalyptus areas to stop fires.

description:
Planting trees in Flanders (Belgium) with Natuurpunt

Who is Natuurpunt?
Natuurpunt is a Flemish NGO dedicated to nature conservation for more than half a century. We specialise in creating and managing nature reserves. We manage 26.000 ha of nature in Flanders at this moment. To do this we can count on several professional field teams and on many thousands of volunteers, who make out the very heart of our organisation. We organise courses, field trips, walks; we study nature and gather scientific information; we give nature a voice when talking to local and national politicians and other organisations.
We have gathered a lot of experience in what we do. The government and even the European Commission see us as a reliable partner. They grant us subsidies and projects.
123.000 families are member of our organization and pay an annual contribution to support our work. 

Urgency
Forests everywhere in the world are having a difficult time. Flanders is the less wooded region in Europe. Only 11% of our region is wooded. The existing woods are getting smaller and less biodiverse.
That is a problem because woods can play an important part in tackling climate change. They capture carbon dioxide, produce oxygen, retain water and regulate temperature. 
That is why Natuurpunt has made the commitment to create 700 ha of woods in Flanders by 2024. That means 1.750.000 trees! Half of it will be planted, the other half will be natural regeneration.

Quality forests
We do not want the plant trees, but woods. A wood is ecosystem with a diversity of plants and animals. We choose the right trees and plants for the right soils. That is where our knowhow on ecology comes in handy. We choose plants that are typical for our region, not exotic plants. Our woods are open for everybody to enjoy them for walking, cycling, sporting, soft recreation, �

Planting trees
In order to realise our goals we have set up a Fund �Woods for everyone.� In that fund we collect donations and contributions from individuals and companies or organisations. With those financial means and the government grants we can buy terrains and plant trees. We always try to own the land on which we plant so we can guarantee that the new wood will always stay a wood. We also take care of the wood in the year following the planting. 
We ask for the necessary authorisations, we order the correct trees and then we organise a planting day. We invite people to come and help us with the planting: neighbours, volunteers, donors, schools, youth organisations, companies, �

degradationCause: Primary cause of degradation is over pasturing of cattle but also climate change has  created more severe dry seasons that kill many more saplings than in the past.  Thus the forests have not been able to self-sustain.
description: The hills surrounding El Magistral have been under stress for decades from expanding local population and defortestation due to cattle pasturing and climate change factors.  We have been working with this community for several years now in trying to replenish these beautiful forests.  Although they are supportive and heavily committed, El Magistral is a small village that does not have the resources to do the project themselves.  The trees we plant will reduce soil erosion, increase the amount of rain water that replenishes underground water reserves and will sequester carbon dioxide from the atmosphere for years to come.  Please help us with this important project!

description:
The Taita hills are the northernmost end of the Eastern Arc, a chain of ancient mountains running from S.E Kenya to S Tanzania. The Hills have a unique, highly threatened forest biota and are the highest-ranking conservation priority in Kenya. Deforestation is estimated at 98% and currently, only 12 highly fragmented forests remain with a combined total area of 500Ha only. The extreme levels of habitat loss, reduced forest connectivity and high levels of forest disturbance are causing severe threats to the Taita Hills' unique biodiversity.   
Since 2014, in collaboration with other partners, we have focused our conservation efforts in protecting and restoring the cloud forest as well as enhancing ecological connectivity for these threatened endemic species. The science-driven multi-tactic approach involves Planting of indigenous tree species on degraded public land, eradication of invasive/exotic species and replacing with indigenous species, Land purchase on critical sites to protect species and connect habitats, policy and advocacy, Awareness and conducting research that guide on proper conservation approach.
With full involvement of the local community and the local government, we have identified 32 patches of degraded public land (c.380Ha) that range from 3-20ha and well distributed within the Taita Hills which form our target restoration areas. Through our restoration pilot project, we have formulated a practical approach that will see virtually all the identified 32 patches restored with natural vegetation in a span of 18 years. We are currently  restoring 20 hectares located in 3 strategic sites. 
If the restoration of all the targeted sites is achieved together with the targeted land purchase, we shall achieve a 100% increase of the existing natural forest. this will significantly increase habitats and highly enhance forest connectivity thus solving the conservation puzzle of threatened species of both flora and fauna. Our restoration work will also contribute towards everting climate change and in ensuring increased water supply that will benefit local communities among other benefits.

degradationCause: Clearing of forests and wetlands for cattle rearing
description: For over four years, FBC and its allies have been building capacity and supporting the local fishermen community of Barbacoas with a  tree nursery and forest restoration. The aim is to provide a source of income through nature conservation to improve their livelihoods. In 2020, FBC expanded its El Silencio Natural Reserve to a former cattle ranching area that neighbors the community. The aim of this project is to raise funds for the community to provide tree seedlings and pay for labor to restore cattle pastures in two areas: 1) the border of the main stream in the area in order to improve habitat for water and terrestrial animals, and where the community can carry out community-based ecotourism; and 2) the basin of a deep well where the community pumps out their household water through a solar system that our foundation supported building in 2019. Restoring the forest cover of the basin would ensure water provision for the future and improve the community's resilience to climate change.

degradationCause: In the last 30 years, people have cut down almost all their trees. The root causes of deforestation is the rising cost of Charcoal. One tree for charcoal is $50 for a family. So trees are cut down to make lives better. Less rain means less farming crops, so more trees are cut. 1 mature tree is $200!
description:
Much of the rainforest in Haiti has been cut down over the last 50 years. Here�s how our project is restoring the forest by empowering local communities.

Our agronomist visits villages requesting reforestation and presents the importance of trees/forest to communities at churches and schools, such as:

1. Where and how to plant each kind of tree
2. What trees provide to the ecosystem and to the people� he talks a lot about bringing back the songs of birds pulling people heart strings
3. How trees build the water table and hold soil for crops
Composting
4. Companion planting with crops, shade grown crops etc.
5. How to best stop goats from eating the seedlings.

longTermPlan: Six months after each planting we survey the land and seedling survival. A community committee is formed to plan for continued reforestation. As the projects grow, so does community involvement. The knowledge we share is spread throughout the community, and financial independence is achieved.
mainChallenge: The main challenge is to reverse the negative impact deforestation has had on the lives of Haitian people.We work within communities asking for financial and educational support to expand their reforestation efforts. 2 tree nurseries are established that employ mostly women from the community.

description:
ITPA was born in 1998, from the initiative of environmentalists committed to guaranteeing the protection of one of the last and most conserved fragments of Atlantic Forest, in Rio de Janeiro, the Tingu� Biological Reserve.
We are currently the largest environmental organization based in the state of Rio, where we maintain dozens of work fronts, with more than 70 employees, and we have already planted 3.5 million trees. We are involved in forest restoration actions, creation and implementation of natural reserves, natural tourism, among others.
The ITPA focuses on the bioregion called the Tingu� Bocaina Biodiversity Corridor. This is the most critical fragmentation region of the largest Atlantic Forest continuum in the country and comprises the main springs that supply water to the metropolitan region of Rio de Janeiro (about 10 million inhabitants).
ITPA maintains many areas in the process of forest restoration, with more than 3.5 million native trees in partnership with almost 100 rural landowners, through voluntary area assignment contracts and payment contracts for environmental services. It also maintains the largest brigade for preventing and fighting forest fires, with very satisfactory results for natural regeneration.
At the same time, we develop environmental education projects with schools in order to raise awareness and directly involve young people in the regeneration process of the Atlantic Forest.
It should be noted that ITPA has a headquarters with all the infrastructure for educational and forest restoration actions, integrated with a Private Reserve of Natural Heritage and with buildings built in an ecological way.

description:
Planting fruit trees in the reserved areas of Handeni District's public schools in Tanzania is a wonderful initiative for several reasons. Firstly, it will providea sustainable source of nutritious fruits for the students. This can greatly enhance their diet and overall health, as fruits are rich in vitamins, minerals, and antioxidants.

Secondly, planting fruit trees can serve as an educational tool for the students. They willa sustainable source of nutritious food for the students. Fruit trees such as mango, avocado, and orange can thrive in the local climate and soil conditions, ensuring a bountiful harvest. This will not only improve the students' diets but also contribute to their overall health and well-being.

In addition to the nutritional benefits, planting fruit trees in school areas will also serve as an educational tool. Students can learn about the importance of trees, the process of planting and caring for them, and the value of environmental conservation. It will instill a sense of responsibility towards nature and foster a connection with the environment.

Furthermore, the presence of fruit trees will create a beautiful and inviting atmosphere within the school premises. Green and lush surroundings will uplift the overall aesthetics and provide a peaceful environment for students to learn and play.

To make this initiative a success, it is crucial to involve the students, teachers, and community members. The school administration can organize tree planting events and workshops to educate everyone about the benefits and proper care of fruit trees. Local agricultural experts can also provide guidance on the appropriate tree species and cultivation techniques.

By planting fruit trees in the reserved areas of public schools in Handeni District, Tanzania, we can nourish the minds and bodies of our students while creating a greener and more sustainable future.

description:
The Mangkutub-Project is a joint reforestation project of BOS Schweiz and the BOS Foundation restoring 50 ha (with a potential up to 971 ha) of burned valuable peatland in Central-Kalimantan, Indonesia. 

The expected climate effect is huge because tropical peatland stores up to 20 times more carbon than non-peat mineral soils. In addition, the rainforests of Borneo, Indonesia belongs to the most biodiverse forests of the world. The Mawas area even sustains one of the largest remaining orangutan populations with an estimated 2550 orangutans inhabiting the forest!

The main focus of the Mawas Program is the protection of wild orangutan habitat and forest restoration by involving the local communities. This includes - apart from the reforestation - the blocking of drainage-canals, the protection from wildfires and the creation of sustainable livelihoods for the local communities. 

The main goal of the project is to ensure the sustainable management of the Mawas area as a peatland orangutan habitat with high conservation value, together with the local communities and other stakeholders as well as the provision of environmental and economic benefits for the surrounding community.

The price for 1 tree (7.65 CHF) includes 1.) the collection of seeds in the area, 2.) the production of the seedling itself (in project-owned tree nurseries), 3.) the planting of the seedling and 4.) 5 years of care (including the removal of seedlings that die) by local communities.

Donations to BOS Schweiz are tax deductible in Switzerland and elsewhere (depending on your tax system)!

The price for 1 tree (7.65 CHF) includes 1.) the collection of seeds in the area, 2.) the production of the seedling itself (in project-owned tree nurseries), 3.) the planting of the seedling and 4.) 5 years of care (including the removal of seedlings that die) by local communities. BOS Schweiz is tax deductible in Switzerland!', 'id': 'site_VqLYSNlKf52H0lg', 'status': 'planting'}}]

description:
Colombia's Western Andes is a very special place � At least 70 percent is cloud forests and the rest is grasslands. About a sixth of the world�s biodiversity � perhaps two million species of plants, animals, fungi and microorganisms � can be found in the region. Remarkably, only about 10 percent have been identified.

But, like coral reefs and glaciers, it is among the most vulnerable to the dual impacts of climate change and human population pressures. As our planet�s climate systems continue to be altered, it is very likely that some or many of the species found in cloud forests will be lost forever. 

The forests have become fragmented and degraded as agriculture moves up the mountainside and penetrates deeper into the lowlands, encroaching on the solitude.  Sadly, the effects of climate change are already apparent here. As a result, many cloud forest species have started to migrate upslope to maintain a favorable climate. However, their routes are often blocked by a degraded and fragmented landscape. 

Saving Nature is working with the Hummingbird Conservancy to protect, connect, and restore the most important areas for biodiversity. In doing so, we�ll help create a large protected area for endemic and threatened species from the east and west. Restoring the forest from degraded land will also soak up a lot of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere � this is a warm, wet place where trees grow quickly. By the same token, heavy rainfall on steep mountain slopes means these areas erode quickly once they lose their forests.

description:
AYUDH Europe is an international youth movement, dedicated to empowering young people to contribute to a peaceful and sustainable world and become compassionate leaders with a sense of tolerance, solidarity and global responsibility.

Not tax deduction information available yet!

As such, AYUDH has been dedicated to plant over 3000 trees in the last 14 years.

In July 2018, AYUDH launched "Trees for Peace", a new tree planting campaign, celebrating the full dedication of AYUDH Europe to renew its efforts towards tree planting.

Trees for Peace is more than a tree-planting campaign, it combines concrete climate action with education for sustainable lifestyles, while fostering a community of young Europeans, dedicated to making a difference. From Lisbon to Munich to Copenhagen � across ten European countries, our youth volunteers meet to plant together.

Each Trees for Peace activity is carried out by young people (aged 15 � 30) and is combined with workshops on sustainable living. We believe that planting trees is a powerful way to bring people together, experience community, and strengthen a sense of global responsibility and leadership in young people. It can inspire youth from all backgrounds to be active citizens, bringing them together to build a more sustainable and peaceful future.

Our objectives are:

1) Through tree planting initiatives, give to youth all over Europe an important toolkit of skills and values such as planning, management, sense of active citizenship, social and ecological awareness.

2) Turning tree planting in a socially useful activity, by fostering community building and collaborating local administrations by realising cost-free green areas and community fruit orchard, supporting in particular those administrations (e.g. municipalities) which are unable to create afforestation project due lack of budget availability.

3) Create a concrete impact on environmental protection, by:
- a) Planting trees which absorb our CO2 emissions, reducing our carbon footprint;
- b) Planting native species to the European landscape, preserving the original European biodiversity and planting endangered or rare indigenous species which are threatened by human activity, pests or by alien invasive species;
- c) Creating projects of soil restoration, using tree planting as a tool to fight back soil erosion caused by natural adversities (floods, landslides, drought) and degradation by human activities.

Our goal is to plant over 1000 trees by 2021.

When the goal will be reached, the campaign will continue and a new goal will be set.

Around one quarter of the forest area has already been de-forested over the last 3 years. WaldLiebe meets these challenges as a holistic multidimensional project for the future of the native forest.
description:
THE AREA
The Taunus is a mountain range in the center of Germany, located north of Frankfurt. 

THE CHALLENGE
As in many other areas, heat, storm damage and the bark beetle have caused some terrible damage to the Taunus forests in the past years. More than a million trees have been lost and need to be replaced by new ones able to cope with the changing climatic conditions.
The biggest challenge, however, is the necessary change of awareness for the many roles of the forest beyond the function as timber provider.

THE ANSWER
The WaldLiebe is an officially recognized nonprofit organization (�Gemeinn�tziger Verein�) and meets these challenges as a holistic multidimensional project for the future of our native forest.
It is absolutely neutral regarding politics, religion and special interest groups and led by an elected board.
It works very closely with the local authorities representing the community as owner of the forest but remains strictly independent of any influence on its decision making.

WaldLiebe is based on the close integration of its members, individual citizens, associations, schools & daycare centers, businesses and the Neu-Anspach city administration for a common goal.
It organizes many different activities like tree planting and protection, establishing a new tree nursery unique to the region, renaturation of water sources, an art hiking trail, tree sculptures, bee trees and other activities to provide active help and protection for the forest and to increase awareness for the many different functions of the forest.
The project continues to develop dynamically and has developed into an integration point for the local population.
Activities are led by forest and marketing professionals and supported by scientific advisors.

description:
Endangered Trees is a community enterprise and agricultural cooperative in Surin / Thailand with the mission of planting endangered tree species, reforest expired rice patties and rubber tree plantations and organize tree planting events for the local population. Our aim is to mitigate global warming, bring benefits to the local population and save endangered trees from extinction.

Many rubber tree plantations that were established in the boom years (2005 to 2011) are not profitable and farmers want to cut the trees and sell the log. Perfect opportunity for our foundation to plant new trees, and turning the monoculture into a forest and diverse ecosystem. The established rubber trees provide perfect shade for the young saplings to grow. Once the new trees are three to five years old, some of the rubber trees may be cut down.

Rice paddies become expired or abandoned, when the young generation does not want to continue with the rice farming business their parents have pursued, and parents are too old to take care of the plantations. This is an opportunity for Endangered Trees to plant micro-forests, with endangered tree species, providing the young generation with an income through sustainable forestry. 

There are also many rice paddies in the area that are too wet, meaning water being stuck in the paddy for months after the rainy season, and tractors are unable to cut the rice. Those paddies are often abandoned up by farmers, as cutting by hand is arduous and unprofitable job. With this more opportunities arise for Endangered Trees to plant micro-forests on those abandoned rice paddies.

In addition, Endangered Trees foundation organizes tree planting events for the local population and plant trees on public land, around municipality lakes, with help of the mayor and the local schools. 

Endangered Trees is also involved in the primary school in Baan Cha Niang Village, organizing many projects from English teaching to tree planting projects with kids aged 5 to 12.

Each student aged 11 and 12 will godfather a tree and take care of it as part of our philanthropic mission.

In addition, for each tree that is planted by our organization, one Baht is paid into the student's piggy bank.

degradationCause: Tea factories consume enormous amounts of firewood to cure tea, buying it from community members. Charcoal burning and timber harvesting are other income generation activities for the farmers that leads to environmental degradation. On top of this, initiative for planting trees is little.
description: Agroforestry efforts directly contribute towards achieving two fundamental goals: improve the livelihoods of vulnerable communities while restoring the environment. According to their size of land, smallholder farmers receive differentbeneficial tree species such as fruit trees, trees that will provide firewood, and that will provide fodder for cattle, among others. At the same time, these trees regenerate the soil that leads to increased productivity and attracts rain.Nevertheless, we do not only deliver trees to farmers: we also work with them closely, providing training on how to take care of them, the importance of trees, and climate change. This way, sustainability of the efforts is supported, as communities raise their levels of awareness and contribute to protecting the environment.In addition, after a few months after planting, we approach the site and monitor the trees, assessing their survival rate and appearance.

description:
The SeaTrees Mangrove Forests in Mida Creek and Marereni, Kenya aims to restores 100+ hectares of degraded mangrove forest within the Malindi Watamu National Marine Park and Reserve - a UNESCO Designated Biosphere Area + one of the world�s oldest Marine Protected Areas.


In partnership with the local community, 2 million mangrove SeaTrees will be planted throughout the Mida Creek and Marereni region.


Mida Creek and Marereni are critical stopover sites for migratory birds, and are recognized International Bird Areas. Together with Arabuko-Sokoke Forest, the area forms a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve.


Mida Creek and Marereni are home to critical sea turtle habitat and nesting areas, are used as a nursing ground for Humpback Whales, and have a large resident population of Indo-pacific Bottlenose Dolphin. A large portion of Watamu Marine National Park has also been internationally recognized as an Important Marine Mammal Area (IMMA) by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN).


Both projects support the surrounding local communities - providing food, revenue from tourism, and protection from storm surges and sea level rise.


In the past, mangrove trees have been illegally harvested for lumber and charcoal production, due to local economic pressures. Working with local communities to provide jobs reduces this pressure and allows impacted areas to be regenerated by planting and protecting native mangroves species. Planting is done in alignment with the UNEP / Guidelines on Mangrove Ecosystem Restoration for the Western Indian Ocean Region.


SeaTrees has partnered with COBEC (Community Based Environmental Conservation), a community-based organization founded in 2005 in Kenya � focused on local "grass-roots" ocean conservation efforts.


COBEC's main programs were implemented with the support of local communities and government stakeholders who have focused on mangrove forest restoration and Sea Turtle conservation.


This project employs more than 350 people within the local community which in turn drives other Sustainable Development benefits produced by the project. These communities are educated on the environmental and economic importance of these ecosystems, and employed to grow seedlings, collect mangrove propagules, plant mangroves, and monitor the growth of the trees.


In addition to the local communities around Mida Creek and Marereni, COBEC has partnerships with a range of other important local stakeholders to improve the longer-term success of the project and the survival of the trees being planted. This includes: Kenya Wildlife Service, Kenya Forest Service, Kenya Fisheries Service, Kenya Forestry Research Institute, and Watamu Marine Association.

description: YAKUM partners with indigenous communities to protect forest territory and build cultural, medicinal and food sovereignty, through reforestation with carefully selected native tree species and territory mapping. Our work revitalises traditional knowledge and consumption of native foods, through reforestation using over 100 species of Amazonian fruit, nut and palm tree species. Our planting sites are located within Kichwa, Cofan, Siekopai and Shuar territories, are carried out in �minga� community work sessions where children, adults and elders come together to plant with us. Tree species are selected for nutritional and cultural importance for the community.

degradationCause: Urban green infrastructure is unequally distributed across income and race geographies in South Africa, and Thembisa is no exception. Spatial inequalities are mirrored in both public and private green space. Green space inequity has been maintained and entrenched since Apartheid.
description: Through this project, our planting partner will collaborate with 10  schools in Johannesburg to establish 10 indigenous urban forests at the schools. We aim to provide learners, educators and community members with the knowledge and practical horticulture skills required to plan, establish, maintain and extend urban greening . The programme also encourages ecological awareness, environmental responsibility and economic empowerment for the school, community and cultivates future green leaders. The core of the project is to establish a centralized, school-based tree nursery that will grow trees for the 10 schools. Partnering organizations will mentor the students, from teaching them to identify plants, passing on horticultural skills and assisting with urban forest, to general exposure in the horticultural industry.

description: Through this project, our planting partner will collaborate with 10 schools in the Gurgaon city of India in planting fruit trees for food stability and climate mitigation. The trees will be planted by youth, with the support from Sustainable Green Initiative, teachers, administration, and community members. As part of the project, the students will learn first-hand from Sustainable Green Initiative staff about the benefits of trees to mitigate the impacts of climate change.

description:
The re-greening movement is a focurssed  strategies under The Kilimanjaro Corsortium for Development and Environment, aims to particulaly to restore and resustain tree as one of the necessary and urgent solution in adressing the effects of climate changes and ecological destruction. Quntitavely, the rate and speed of deforestation due to human and economic factors, is pathetic. 
Consiquently, the Kilimanjaro Consortium for Developent and Environment (KCDE), considers re-greening movement as one of it�s key priorities in achieving its fundamental objectives, vision and mission. These are summed up in the 17 Sustainable Development Goals.
The key beneficieries up to now (2021) have mainly been identified as churches and educational institutions, KCDE has been giving environmental seminars and donating   different trees seedilings for the regreening goals. Up to now (2021) we have planted 3,860 trees. These include a wide variaty of fruits, food, timber and shade providing trees. Biologicaly, these trees provide also oxigen and good weather to humans and non-humans.

Breafy stated, our long-term strategy, is to engage more stakeholders both private and public to our re-greening movement  and  philosophy  as credible practicals ways and meeans in reducing the ever worsening multiple catatstrophic effects o climate change and unsustainable livelihoods hardhiting both soil flora (plants), soil fauna (animals ) as a whole. Join us now, Stop talking. Let us through us and with us make a difference.
